attach.desc: Gives the address of an associated document for the event.

categories.desc: Gives the name of a category or tag that the event could be classified as.

class.desc: Gives the access classification of the information regarding the event.

comment.desc: Gives a comment regarding the event.

contact.desc: Gives the contact information for the event.

created.desc: Gives the date and time at which the event information was first created in a calendaring system.

description.desc: Gives a detailed description of the event.

dtend.desc: Gives the date and time by which the event ends.

dtstart.desc: Gives the date and time at which the event starts.

duration.desc: Gives the duration of the event.

exdate.desc: Gives a date and time at which the event does not occur despite the recurrence rules.

geo.desc: Gives the geographical position of the event.

last-modified.desc: Gives the date and time at which the event information was last modified in a calendaring system.

location.desc: Gives the location of the event.

rdate.desc: Gives a date and time at which the event recurs.

resources.desc: Gives a resource that will be needed for the event.

rrule.desc: Gives a rule for finding dates and times at which the event occurs.

sequence.desc: Gives a revision number for the event information.

status.desc: Gives the confirmation status of the event.

summary.desc: Gives a short summary of the event.

transp.desc: Gives whether the event is to be considered as consuming time on a calendar, for the purpose of free-busy time searches.

uid.desc: Gives a globally unique identifier corresponding to the event.

url.desc: Gives a URL for the event.

http://microformats.org/profile/hcard.desc: A person's or organization's contact information.
http://microformats.org/profile/hcard.label: vCard

adr.desc: Gives the delivery address of the person or organization.

country-name.desc: Gives the country name component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

extended-address.desc: Gives an additional component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

locality.desc: Gives the locality component (e.g. city) of the delivery address of the person or organization.

post-office-box.desc: Gives the post office box component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

postal-code.desc: Gives the postal code component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

region.desc: Gives the region component (e.g. state or province) of the delivery address of the person or organization.

street-address.desc: Gives the street address component of the delivery address of the person or organization.

type.desc: Gives the type of delivery address.

home.desc: Indicates a delivery address for a residence.

work.desc: Indicates a delivery address for a place of work.

agent.desc: Gives the contact information of another person who will act on behalf of the person or organization.

anniversary.desc: Gives the birth date of the person or organization.

bday.desc: Gives the birth date of the person or organization.

categories.desc: Gives the name of a category or tag that the person or organization could be classified as.

email.desc: Gives the e-mail address of the person or organization.

fn.desc: Gives the formatted text corresponding to the name of the person or organization.

gender-identity.desc: Gives the gender identity of the person.

geo.desc: Gives the geographical position of the person or organization.

impp.desc: Gives a URL for instant messaging and presence protocol communications with the person or organization.

kind.desc: Describes what kind of contact the item represents.

group.desc: Indicates multiple entities (e.g. a mailing list).

individual.desc: Indicates a single entity (e.g. a person).

location.desc: Indicates a geographical place (e.g. an office building).

org.desc: Indicates a single entity that is not a person (e.g. a company).

lang.desc: Gives a language understood by the person or organization.

logo.desc: Gives the logo of the person or organization.

member.desc: Gives a URL that represents a member of the group.

n.desc: Gives the structured name of the person or organization.

additional-name.desc: Gives the any additional names of the person.

family-name.desc: Gives the family name of the person, or the full name of the organization.

given-name.desc: Gives the given-name of the person.

honorific-prefix.desc: Gives the honorific prefix of the person.

honorific-suffix.desc: Gives the honorific suffix of the person.

nickname.desc: Gives the nickname of the person or organization.

note.desc: Gives supplemental information or a comment about the person or organization.

org.desc: Gives the name and units of the organization.

organization-name.desc: Gives the name of the organization.

organization-unit.desc: Gives the name of the organization unit.

photo.desc: Gives a photograph of the person or organization.

related.desc: Gives a relationship to another entity.

rel.desc: Gives the relationship between the entity and the related entity.

agent.desc: Another entity that acts on behalf of this entity.

url.desc: Gives the URL for the related entity.

rev.desc: Gives the revision date and time of the contact information.

role.desc: Gives the role, occupation, or business category of the person or organization.

sex.desc: Gives the biological sex of the person.

sound.desc: Gives a sound file relating to the person or organization.

tel.desc: Gives the telephone number of the person or organization.

type.desc: Gives the type of telephone number.

pager.desc: Indicates a paging device telephone number.

text.desc: Indicates that the telephone number supports text messages (SMS).

textphone.desc: Indicates a telecommunication device for people with hearing or speech difficulties.

video.desc: Indicates a video conferencing telephone number.

work.desc: Indicates a telephone number for a place of work.

value.desc: Gives the actual telephone number of the person or organization.

title.desc: Gives the job title, functional position or function of the person or organization.

tz.desc: Gives the time zone of the person or organization.

uid.desc: Gives a globally unique identifier corresponding to the person or organization.

url.desc: Gives a URL relating to the person or organization.

http://n.whatwg.org/work.desc: A work (e.g. an article, an image, a video, a song, etc).
http://n.whatwg.org/work.label: Licensing works

author.desc: Gives the name or contact information of one of the authors or creators of the work.

license.desc: Identifies one of the licenses under which the work is available.

title.desc: Gives the name of the work.

http://schema.org/APIReference.desc: Reference documentation for application programming interfaces (APIs).

assembly.desc: Library file name e.g., mscorlib.dll, system.web.dll.

executableLibraryName.desc: Library file name e.g., mscorlib.dll, system.web.dll.

programmingModel.desc: Indicates whether API is managed or unmanaged.

targetPlatform.desc: Type of app development: phone, Metro style, desktop, XBox, etc.

http://schema.org/AcceptAction.desc: The act of committing to/adopting an object..

http://schema.org/AchieveAction.desc: The act of accomplishing something via     previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing     process.

http://schema.org/Action.desc:
An action performed by a direct agent and indirect     participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location     with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action     may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies     the exact expectation of each argument/role.
      See also blog post
      and Actions overview document.

actionStatus.desc: Indicates the current disposition of the Action.

agent.desc: The direct performer or driver of the action (animate or inanimate). e.g. *John* wrote a book.

endTime.desc:
The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*.

Note that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

error.desc: For failed actions, more information on the cause of the failure.

instrument.desc: The object that helped the agent perform the action. e.g. John wrote a book with *a pen*.

location.desc: The location of the event, organization or action.

object.desc: The object upon the action is carried out, whose state is kept intact or changed. Also known as the semantic roles patient, affected or undergoer (which change their state) or theme (which doesn't). e.g. John read *a book*.

participant.desc: Other co-agents that participated in the action indirectly. e.g. John wrote a book with *Steve*.

result.desc: The result produced in the action. e.g. John wrote *a book*.

startTime.desc:
The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December.

Note that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

target.desc: Indicates a target EntryPoint for an Action.

http://schema.org/ActivateAction.desc: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).

http://schema.org/AddAction.desc: The act of editing by adding an object to a collection.

http://schema.org/AdministrativeArea.desc: A geographical region under the jurisdiction of a particular government.

http://schema.org/AggregateOffer.desc: When a single product is associated with multiple offers (for example, the same pair of shoes is offered by different merchants), then AggregateOffer can be used.

highPrice.desc: The highest price of all offers available.

lowPrice.desc: The lowest price of all offers available.

offerCount.desc: The number of offers for the product.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, or give away tickets to an event.

http://schema.org/AggregateRating.desc: The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.

itemReviewed.desc: The item that is being reviewed/rated.

ratingCount.desc: The count of total number of ratings.

reviewCount.desc: The count of total number of reviews.

http://schema.org/AgreeAction.desc: The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/Airline.desc: An organization that provides flights for passengers.

boardingPolicy.desc: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

iataCode.desc: IATA identifier for an airline or airport.
IATA identifier for an airline or airport.

http://schema.org/AlignmentObject.desc: An intangible item that describes an alignment between a learning resource and a node in an educational framework.

alignmentType.desc: A category of alignment between the learning resource and the framework node. Recommended values include: 'assesses', 'teaches', 'requires', 'textComplexity', 'readingLevel', 'educationalSubject', and 'educationLevel'.

educationalFramework.desc: The framework to which the resource being described is aligned.

targetDescription.desc: The description of a node in an established educational framework.

targetName.desc: The name of a node in an established educational framework.

targetUrl.desc: The URL of a node in an established educational framework.

http://schema.org/AllocateAction.desc: The act of organizing tasks/objects/events by associating resources to it.

purpose.desc: A goal towards an action is taken. Can be concrete or abstract.

http://schema.org/AnatomicalStructure.desc: Any part of the human body, typically a component of an anatomical system. Organs, tissues, and cells are all anatomical structures.

associatedPathophysiology.desc: If applicable, a description of the pathophysiology associated with the anatomical system, including potential abnormal changes in the mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions of the system.

bodyLocation.desc: Location in the body of the anatomical structure.

connectedTo.desc: Other anatomical structures to which this structure is connected.

diagram.desc: An image containing a diagram that illustrates the structure and/or its component substructures and/or connections with other structures.

partOfSystem.desc: The anatomical or organ system that this structure is part of.

relatedCondition.desc: A medical condition associated with this anatomy.

relatedTherapy.desc: A medical therapy related to this anatomy.

subStructure.desc: Component (sub-)structure(s) that comprise this anatomical structure.

http://schema.org/AnatomicalSystem.desc: An anatomical system is a group of anatomical structures that work together to perform a certain task. Anatomical systems, such as organ systems, are one organizing principle of anatomy, and can includes circulatory, digestive, endocrine, integumentary, immune, lymphatic, muscular, nervous, reproductive, respiratory, skeletal, urinary, vestibular, and other systems.

associatedPathophysiology.desc: If applicable, a description of the pathophysiology associated with the anatomical system, including potential abnormal changes in the mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions of the system.

comprisedOf.desc: The underlying anatomical structures, such as organs, that comprise the anatomical system.

relatedCondition.desc: A medical condition associated with this anatomy.

relatedStructure.desc: Related anatomical structure(s) that are not part of the system but relate or connect to it, such as vascular bundles associated with an organ system.

relatedTherapy.desc: A medical therapy related to this anatomy.

http://schema.org/Answer.desc: An answer offered to a question; perhaps correct, perhaps opinionated or wrong.

http://schema.org/AppendAction.desc: The act of inserting at the end if an ordered collection.

http://schema.org/ApplyAction.desc: The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it. .

http://schema.org/ApprovedIndication.desc: An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.

http://schema.org/ArriveAction.desc: The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from an fromLocation, optionally with participants.

http://schema.org/Artery.desc: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood away from the heart.

arterialBranch.desc: The branches that comprise the arterial structure.

source.desc: The anatomical or organ system that the artery originates from.

supplyTo.desc: The area to which the artery supplies blood.

http://schema.org/Article.desc:
An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.

      See also blog post.

articleBody.desc: The actual body of the article.

articleSection.desc: Articles may belong to one or more 'sections' in a magazine or newspaper, such as Sports, Lifestyle, etc.

pageEnd.desc: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

pageStart.desc: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

pagination.desc: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

wordCount.desc: The number of words in the text of the Article.

http://schema.org/AskAction.desc: The act of posing a question / favor to someone..

question.desc: A sub property of object. A question.

http://schema.org/AssessAction.desc: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

http://schema.org/AssignAction.desc: The act of allocating an action/event/task to some destination (someone or something).

http://schema.org/Audience.desc: Intended audience for an item, i.e. the group for whom the item was created.

audienceType.desc: The target group associated with a given audience (e.g. veterans, car owners, musicians, etc.).

geographicArea.desc: The geographic area associated with the audience.

transcript.desc: If this MediaObject is an AudioObject or VideoObject, the transcript of that object.

http://schema.org/AuthorizeAction.desc: The act of granting permission to an object.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/BefriendAction.desc: The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically..

blogPost.desc: A posting that is part of this blog.

blogPosts.desc: The postings that are part of this blog.

http://schema.org/BloodTest.desc: A medical test performed on a sample of a patient's blood.

http://schema.org/BoardingPolicyType.desc: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.

http://schema.org/BodyOfWater.desc: A body of water, such as a sea, ocean, or lake.

http://schema.org/Bone.desc: Rigid connective tissue that comprises up the skeletal structure of the human body.

numberOfPages.desc: The number of pages in the book.

http://schema.org/BookFormatType.desc: The publication format of the book.

http://schema.org/BookSeries.desc: A series of books. Included books can be indicated with the hasPart property.

http://schema.org/BorrowAction.desc: The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction..

lender.desc: A sub property of participant. The person that lends the object being borrowed.

http://schema.org/BrainStructure.desc: Any anatomical structure which pertains to the soft nervous tissue functioning as the coordinating center of sensation and intellectual and nervous activity.

http://schema.org/Brand.desc: A brand is a name used by an organization or business person for labeling a product, product group, or similar.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

http://schema.org/BreadcrumbList.desc:
A BreadcrumbList is an ItemList consisting of a chain of linked Web pages, typically described using at least their URL and their name, and typically ending with the current page.
      
      
      The 'position' property is used to reconstruct the order of the items in a BreadcrumbList.
      The convention is that a breadcrumb list has an itemListOrder of ItemListOrderAscending (lower values listed first), and that the
      first items in this list correspond to the "top" or beginning of the breadcrumb trail, e.g. with a site or section homepage.
      The specific values of 'position' are not assigned meaning for a BreadcrumbList, but they should be integers, e.g. beginning
      with '1' for the first item in the list.

http://schema.org/BroadcastChannel.desc: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

broadcastChannelId.desc: The unique address by which the BroadcastService can be identified in a provider lineup. In US, this is typically a number.

broadcastServiceTier.desc: The type of service required to have access to the channel (e.g. Standard or Premium).

providesBroadcastService.desc: The BroadcastService offered on this channel.

http://schema.org/BroadcastEvent.desc: An over the air or online broadcast event.

isLiveBroadcast.desc: True is the broadcast is of a live event.

http://schema.org/BroadcastService.desc: A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

area.desc: The area within which users can expect to reach the broadcast service.

broadcastAffiliateOf.desc: The media network(s) whose content is broadcast on this station.

broadcastDisplayName.desc: The name displayed in the channel guide. For many US affiliates, it is the network name.

broadcastTimezone.desc: The timezone in ISO 8601 format for which the service bases its broadcasts.

broadcaster.desc: The organization owning or operating the broadcast service.

parentService.desc: A broadcast service to which the broadcast service may belong to such as regional variations of a national channel.

http://schema.org/BusReservation.desc: A reservation for bus travel.Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use http://schema.org/Offer.

http://schema.org/BusTrip.desc: A trip on a commercial bus line.

arrivalBusStop.desc: The stop or station from which the bus arrives.

busName.desc: The name of the bus (e.g. Bolt Express).

busNumber.desc: The unique identifier for the bus.

departureBusStop.desc: The stop or station from which the bus departs.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

http://schema.org/BusinessAudience.desc: A set of characteristics belonging to businesses, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

numberOfEmployees.desc: The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.

yearlyRevenue.desc: The size of the business in annual revenue.

http://schema.org/BusinessEntityType.desc:
A business entity type is a conceptual entity representing the legal form, the size, the main line of business, the position in the value chain, or any combination thereof, of an organization or business person.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Business 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Enduser 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PublicInstitution 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Reseller

http://schema.org/BusinessFunction.desc:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy

http://schema.org/BuyAction.desc: The act of giving money to a seller in exchange for goods or services rendered. An agent buys an object, product, or service from a seller for a price. Reciprocal of SellAction.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

warrantyPromise.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/CableOrSatelliteServic.desc: A service which provides access to media programming like TV or radio. Access may be via cable or satellite.

http://schema.org/Canal.desc: A canal, like the Panama Canal.

http://schema.org/CancelAction.desc: The act of asserting that a future event/action is no longer going to happen..

http://schema.org/Car.desc: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.

http://schema.org/CarUsageType.desc: A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.

http://schema.org/CheckAction.desc: An agent inspects/determines/investigates/inquire or examine an object's accuracy/quality/condition or state.

http://schema.org/CheckInAction.desc: The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their arrival by registering/confirming for a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or at a place (e.g. hotel), possibly resulting in a result (boarding pass, etc)..

http://schema.org/CheckOutAction.desc: The act of an agent communicating (service provider, social media, etc) their departure of a previously reserved service (e.g. flight check in) or place (e.g. hotel)..

http://schema.org/ChooseAction.desc: The act of expressing a preference from a set of options or a large or unbounded set of choices/options.

actionOption.desc: A sub property of object. The options subject to this action.

option.desc: A sub property of object. The options subject to this action.

http://schema.org/CivicStructure.desc: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.

openingHours.desc: The opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.- Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su.- Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as 15:00. - Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. - If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

http://schema.org/Class.desc: A class, also often called a 'Type'; equivalent to rdfs:Class.

supersededBy.desc: Relates a term (i.e. a property, class or enumeration) to one that supersedes it.

http://schema.org/Clip.desc: A short TV or radio program or a segment/part of a program.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

clipNumber.desc: Position of the clip within an ordered group of clips.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

partOfEpisode.desc: The episode to which this clip belongs.

partOfSeason.desc: The season to which this episode belongs.

partOfSeries.desc: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

http://schema.org/Code.desc: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

http://schema.org/CollegeOrUniversity.desc: A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.

http://schema.org/Comment.desc: A comment on an item - for example, a comment on a blog post. The comment's content is expressed via the "text" property, and its topic via "about", properties shared with all CreativeWorks.

downvoteCount.desc: The number of downvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

parentItem.desc: The parent of a question, answer or item in general.

upvoteCount.desc: The number of upvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

http://schema.org/CommentAction.desc: The act of generating a comment about a subject.

resultComment.desc: A sub property of result. The Comment created or sent as a result of this action.

http://schema.org/CommunicateAction.desc: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.

about.desc: The subject matter of the content.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the IETF BCP 47 standard.

language.desc: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/ConfirmAction.desc: The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected..

expectsAcceptanceOf.desc: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

http://schema.org/ContactPoint.desc: A contact point—for example, a Customer Complaints department.

areaServed.desc: The location served by this contact point (e.g., a phone number intended for Europeans vs. North Americans or only within the United States).

availableLanguage.desc: A language someone may use with the item.

contactOption.desc: An option available on this contact point (e.g. a toll-free number or support for hearing-impaired callers).

contactType.desc: A person or organization can have different contact points, for different purposes. For example, a sales contact point, a PR contact point and so on. This property is used to specify the kind of contact point.

hoursAvailable.desc: The hours during which this contact point is available.

productSupported.desc: The product or service this support contact point is related to (such as product support for a particular product line). This can be a specific product or product line (e.g. "iPhone") or a general category of products or services (e.g. "smartphones").

http://schema.org/ContactPointOption.desc: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.

http://schema.org/Continent.desc: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).

http://schema.org/ControlAction.desc: An agent controls a device or application.

foodEstablishment.desc: A sub property of location. The specific food establishment where the action occurred.

foodEvent.desc: A sub property of location. The specific food event where the action occurred.

recipe.desc: A sub property of instrument. The recipe/instructions used to perform the action.

tickerSymbol.desc: The exchange traded instrument associated with a Corporation object. The tickerSymbol is expressed as an exchange and an instrument name separated by a space character. For the exchange component of the tickerSymbol attribute, we reccommend using the controlled vocaulary of Market Identifier Codes (MIC) specified in ISO15022.

http://schema.org/CreateAction.desc: The act of deliberately creating/producing/generating/building a result out of the agent.

http://schema.org/CreativeWork.desc: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

about.desc: The subject matter of the content.

accessibilityAPI.desc: Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API.

accessibilityControl.desc: Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource.

accessibilityFeature.desc: Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility.

accessibilityHazard.desc: A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3.

accountablePerson.desc: Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

alternativeHeadline.desc: A secondary title of the CreativeWork.

associatedMedia.desc: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

author.desc: The author of this content. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

character.desc: Fictional person connected with a creative work.

citation.desc: A citation or reference to another creative work, such as another publication, web page, scholarly article, etc.

commentCount.desc: The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.

contentLocation.desc: The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.

contentRating.desc: Official rating of a piece of content—for example,'MPAA PG-13'.

contributor.desc: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork.

copyrightHolder.desc: The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.

copyrightYear.desc: The year during which the claimed copyright for the CreativeWork was first asserted.

creator.desc: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

dateCreated.desc: The date on which the CreativeWork was created.

dateModified.desc: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified.

discussionUrl.desc: A link to the page containing the comments of the CreativeWork.

editor.desc: Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.

educationalAlignment.desc: An alignment to an established educational framework.

educationalUse.desc: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

encoding.desc: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.

encodings.desc: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork.

exampleOfWork.desc: A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.

genre.desc: Genre of the creative work or group.

hasPart.desc: Indicates a CreativeWork that is (in some sense) a part of this CreativeWork.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the IETF BCP 47 standard.

interactivityType.desc: The predominant mode of learning supported by the learning resource. Acceptable values are 'active', 'expositive', or 'mixed'.

isBasedOnUrl.desc: A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources. For example, http://example.com/great-multiplication-intro.html.

isFamilyFriendly.desc: Indicates whether this content is family friendly.

isPartOf.desc: Indicates a CreativeWork that this CreativeWork is (in some sense) part of.

keywords.desc: Keywords or tags used to describe this content. Multiple entries in a keywords list are typically delimited by commas.

learningResourceType.desc: The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.

license.desc: A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.

mainEntity.desc: Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.

mentions.desc: Indicates that the CreativeWork contains a reference to, but is not necessarily about a concept.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, or give away tickets to an event.

position.desc: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

producer.desc: The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, tv/radio series etc.).

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

publication.desc: A publication event associated with the item.

publisher.desc: The publisher of the creative work.

publishingPrinciples.desc: Link to page describing the editorial principles of the organization primarily responsible for the creation of the CreativeWork.

recordedAt.desc: The Event where the CreativeWork was recorded. The CreativeWork may capture all or part of the event.

releasedEvent.desc: The place and time the release was issued, expressed as a PublicationEvent.

schemaVersion.desc: Indicates (by URL or string) a particular version of a schema used in some CreativeWork. For example, a document could declare a schemaVersion using an URL such as http://schema.org/version/2.0/ if precise indication of schema version was required by some application.

sourceOrganization.desc: The Organization on whose behalf the creator was working.

text.desc: The textual content of this CreativeWork.

thumbnailUrl.desc: A thumbnail image relevant to the Thing.

timeRequired.desc: Approximate or typical time it takes to work with or through this learning resource for the typical intended target audience, e.g. 'P30M', 'P1H25M'.

translator.desc: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market.

typicalAgeRange.desc: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

version.desc: The version of the CreativeWork embodied by a specified resource.

workExample.desc: Example/instance/realization/derivation of the concept of this creative work. eg. The paperback edition, first edition, or eBook.

http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeason.desc: A media season e.g. tv, radio, video game etc.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

partOfSeries.desc: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

seasonNumber.desc: Position of the season within an ordered group of seasons.

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/CreativeWorkSeries.desc:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind.
          CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike ItemList which
          is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with
          CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals,
          or media such as tv, radio and games).

          

          Specific subtypes are available for describing TVSeries, RadioSeries,
          MovieSeries,
          BookSeries,
          Periodical
          and VideoGameSeries. In each case,
          the hasPart / isPartOf properties
          can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely
          just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

          

          It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group.
          Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply
          properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

http://schema.org/CreditCard.desc:
A credit or debit card type as a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA

http://schema.org/DDxElement.desc: An alternative, closely-related condition typically considered later in the differential diagnosis process along with the signs that are used to distinguish it.

diagnosis.desc: One or more alternative conditions considered in the differential diagnosis process.

distinguishingSign.desc: One of a set of signs and symptoms that can be used to distinguish this diagnosis from others in the differential diagnosis.

http://schema.org/DanceGroup.desc: A dance group—for example, the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater or Riverdance.

dataset.desc: A dataset contained in a catalog.

http://schema.org/DataType.desc: The basic data types such as Integers, Strings, etc.

http://schema.org/Dataset.desc: A body of structured information describing some topic(s) of interest.

catalog.desc: A data catalog which contains a dataset.

datasetTimeInterval.desc: The range of temporal applicability of a dataset, e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 (in ISO 8601 time interval format).

distribution.desc: A downloadable form of this dataset, at a specific location, in a specific format.

includedDataCatalog.desc: A data catalog contained in the dataset.

spatial.desc: The range of spatial applicability of a dataset, e.g. for a dataset of New York weather, the state of New York.

temporal.desc: The range of temporal applicability of a dataset, e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 (in ISO 8601 time interval format).

http://schema.org/DateTime.desc: A combination of date and time of day in the form [-]CCYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss[Z|(+|-)hh:mm] (see Chapter 5.4 of ISO 8601).

http://schema.org/DatedMoneySpecificatio.desc: A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time.

currency.desc: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format).

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

http://schema.org/DayOfWeek.desc:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Monday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Tuesday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Wednesday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Thursday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Friday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Saturday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sunday 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PublicHolidays

http://schema.org/DeactivateAction.desc: The act of stopping or deactivating a device or application (e.g. stopping a timer or turning off a flashlight).

http://schema.org/DefenceEstablishment.desc: A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.

http://schema.org/DeleteAction.desc: The act of editing a recipient by removing one of its objects.

http://schema.org/DeliveryChargeSpecific.desc: The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.

appliesToDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.

ineligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.

http://schema.org/DeliveryEvent.desc: An event involving the delivery of an item.

accessCode.desc: Password, PIN, or access code needed for delivery (e.g. from a locker).

availableFrom.desc: When the item is available for pickup from the store, locker, etc.

availableThrough.desc: After this date, the item will no longer be available for pickup.

hasDeliveryMethod.desc: Method used for delivery or shipping.

http://schema.org/DeliveryMethod.desc:
A delivery method is a standardized procedure for transferring the product or service to the destination of fulfillment chosen by the customer. Delivery methods are characterized by the means of transportation used, and by the organization or group that is the contracting party for the sending organization or person.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeDirectDownload 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeFreight 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeMail 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModeOwnFleet 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DeliveryModePickUp 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

http://schema.org/Demand.desc: A demand entity represents the public, not necessarily binding, not necessarily exclusive, announcement by an organization or person to seek a certain type of goods or services. For describing demand using this type, the very same properties used for Offer apply.

acceptedPaymentMethod.desc: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

advanceBookingRequirement.desc: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

availability.desc: The availability of this item—for example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

availabilityEnds.desc: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availabilityStarts.desc: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availableAtOrFrom.desc: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

availableDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

businessFunction.desc: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

deliveryLeadTime.desc: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods leaving the warehouse.

eligibleCustomerType.desc: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleDuration.desc: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleQuantity.desc: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.

eligibleTransactionVolume.desc: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

gtin12.desc: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin13.desc: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin14.desc: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin8.desc: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

includesObject.desc: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in the offer.

ineligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.

inventoryLevel.desc: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

itemCondition.desc: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

mpn.desc: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

priceSpecification.desc: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

serialNumber.desc: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

sku.desc: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The end of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

warranty.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/DepartAction.desc: The act of  departing from a place. An agent departs from an fromLocation for a destination, optionally with participants.

http://schema.org/DiagnosticLab.desc: A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.

availableTest.desc: A diagnostic test or procedure offered by this lab.

http://schema.org/DiagnosticProcedure.desc: A medical procedure intended primarily for diagnostic, as opposed to therapeutic, purposes.

http://schema.org/Diet.desc: A strategy of regulating the intake of food to achieve or maintain a specific health-related goal.

dietFeatures.desc: Nutritional information specific to the dietary plan. May include dietary recommendations on what foods to avoid, what foods to consume, and specific alterations/deviations from the USDA or other regulatory body's approved dietary guidelines.

endorsers.desc: People or organizations that endorse the plan.

expertConsiderations.desc: Medical expert advice related to the plan.

overview.desc: Descriptive information establishing the overarching theory/philosophy of the plan. May include the rationale for the name, the population where the plan first came to prominence, etc.

physiologicalBenefits.desc: Specific physiologic benefits associated to the plan.

proprietaryName.desc: Proprietary name given to the diet plan, typically by its originator or creator.

risks.desc: Specific physiologic risks associated to the plan.

http://schema.org/DietarySupplement.desc: A product taken by mouth that contains a dietary ingredient intended to supplement the diet. Dietary ingredients may include vitamins, minerals, herbs or other botanicals, amino acids, and substances such as enzymes, organ tissues, glandulars and metabolites.

activeIngredient.desc: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

background.desc: Descriptive information establishing a historical perspective on the supplement. May include the rationale for the name, the population where the supplement first came to prominence, etc.

dosageForm.desc: A dosage form in which this drug/supplement is available, e.g. 'tablet', 'suspension', 'injection'.

isProprietary.desc: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

legalStatus.desc: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

maximumIntake.desc: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

mechanismOfAction.desc: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

nonProprietaryName.desc: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

recommendedIntake.desc: Recommended intake of this supplement for a given population as defined by a specific recommending authority.

safetyConsideration.desc: Any potential safety concern associated with the supplement. May include interactions with other drugs and foods, pregnancy, breastfeeding, known adverse reactions, and documented efficacy of the supplement.

targetPopulation.desc: Characteristics of the population for which this is intended, or which typically uses it, e.g. 'adults'.

http://schema.org/DisagreeAction.desc: The act of expressing a difference of opinion with the object. An agent disagrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/DiscoverAction.desc: The act of discovering/finding an object.

http://schema.org/DislikeAction.desc: The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/Distance.desc: Properties that take Distances as values are of the form '<Number> <Length unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 ft'.

http://schema.org/DonateAction.desc: The act of providing goods, services, or money without compensation, often for philanthropic reasons.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/DoseSchedule.desc: A specific dosing schedule for a drug or supplement.

doseUnit.desc: The unit of the dose, e.g. 'mg'.

doseValue.desc: The value of the dose, e.g. 500.

frequency.desc: How often the dose is taken, e.g. 'daily'.

targetPopulation.desc: Characteristics of the population for which this is intended, or which typically uses it, e.g. 'adults'.

http://schema.org/DownloadAction.desc: The act of downloading an object.

http://schema.org/DrawAction.desc: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

http://schema.org/DriveWheelConfiguratio.desc: A value indicating which roadwheels will receive torque.

http://schema.org/Drug.desc: A chemical or biologic substance, used as a medical therapy, that has a physiological effect on an organism.

activeIngredient.desc: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

administrationRoute.desc: A route by which this drug may be administered, e.g. 'oral'.

alcoholWarning.desc: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of alcohol while taking this drug.

availableStrength.desc: An available dosage strength for the drug.

breastfeedingWarning.desc: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use by breastfeeding mothers.

clincalPharmacology.desc: Description of the absorption and elimination of drugs, including their concentration (pharmacokinetics, pK) and biological effects (pharmacodynamics, pD).

clinicalPharmacology.desc: Description of the absorption and elimination of drugs, including their concentration (pharmacokinetics, pK) and biological effects (pharmacodynamics, pD).

cost.desc: Cost per unit of the drug, as reported by the source being tagged.

dosageForm.desc: A dosage form in which this drug/supplement is available, e.g. 'tablet', 'suspension', 'injection'.

doseSchedule.desc: A dosing schedule for the drug for a given population, either observed, recommended, or maximum dose based on the type used.

drugClass.desc: The class of drug this belongs to (e.g., statins).

foodWarning.desc: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to consumption of specific foods while taking this drug.

interactingDrug.desc: Another drug that is known to interact with this drug in a way that impacts the effect of this drug or causes a risk to the patient. Note: disease interactions are typically captured as contraindications.

isAvailableGenerically.desc: True if the drug is available in a generic form (regardless of name).

isProprietary.desc: True if this item's name is a proprietary/brand name (vs. generic name).

labelDetails.desc: Link to the drug's label details.

legalStatus.desc: The drug or supplement's legal status, including any controlled substance schedules that apply.

mechanismOfAction.desc: The specific biochemical interaction through which this drug or supplement produces its pharmacological effect.

nonProprietaryName.desc: The generic name of this drug or supplement.

overdosage.desc: Any information related to overdose on a drug, including signs or symptoms, treatments, contact information for emergency response.

pregnancyWarning.desc: Any precaution, guidance, contraindication, etc. related to this drug's use during pregnancy.

prescribingInfo.desc: Link to prescribing information for the drug.

prescriptionStatus.desc: Indicates whether this drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter.

relatedDrug.desc: Any other drug related to this one, for example commonly-prescribed alternatives.

warning.desc: Any FDA or other warnings about the drug (text or URL).

http://schema.org/DrugClass.desc: A class of medical drugs, e.g., statins. Classes can represent general pharmacological class, common mechanisms of action, common physiological effects, etc.

drug.desc: A drug in this drug class.

http://schema.org/DrugCost.desc: The cost per unit of a medical drug. Note that this type is not meant to represent the price in an offer of a drug for sale; see the Offer type for that. This type will typically be used to tag wholesale or average retail cost of a drug, or maximum reimbursable cost. Costs of medical drugs vary widely depending on how and where they are paid for, so while this type captures some of the variables, costs should be used with caution by consumers of this schema's markup.

applicableLocation.desc: The location in which the status applies.

costCategory.desc: The category of cost, such as wholesale, retail, reimbursement cap, etc.

costCurrency.desc: The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the drug cost.

costOrigin.desc: Additional details to capture the origin of the cost data. For example, 'Medicare Part B'.

costPerUnit.desc: The cost per unit of the drug.

drugUnit.desc: The unit in which the drug is measured, e.g. '5 mg tablet'.

http://schema.org/DrugCostCategory.desc: Enumerated categories of medical drug costs.

http://schema.org/DrugLegalStatus.desc: The legal availability status of a medical drug.

applicableLocation.desc: The location in which the status applies.

http://schema.org/DrugPregnancyCategory.desc: Categories that represent an assessment of the risk of fetal injury due to a drug or pharmaceutical used as directed by the mother during pregnancy.

http://schema.org/DrugPrescriptionStatus.desc: Indicates whether this drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter.

http://schema.org/DrugStrength.desc: A specific strength in which a medical drug is available in a specific country.

activeIngredient.desc: An active ingredient, typically chemical compounds and/or biologic substances.

availableIn.desc: The location in which the strength is available.

strengthUnit.desc: The units of an active ingredient's strength, e.g. mg.

strengthValue.desc: The value of an active ingredient's strength, e.g. 325.

http://schema.org/EatAction.desc: The act of swallowing solid objects.

http://schema.org/EmergencyService.desc: An emergency service, such as a fire station or ER.

http://schema.org/EmployeeRole.desc: A subclass of OrganizationRole used to describe employee relationships.

baseSalary.desc: The base salary of the job or of an employee in an EmployeeRole.

salaryCurrency.desc: The currency (coded using ISO 4217, http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217 ) used for the main salary information in this job posting or for this employee.

endorsee.desc: A sub property of participant. The person/organization being supported.

http://schema.org/Energy.desc: Properties that take Energy as values are of the form '<Number> <Energy unit of measure>'.

http://schema.org/EngineSpecification.desc: Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.

fuelType.desc: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

http://schema.org/EntryPoint.desc: An entry point, within some Web-based protocol.

actionApplication.desc: An application that can complete the request.

application.desc: An application that can complete the request.

contentType.desc: The supported content type(s) for an EntryPoint response.

encodingType.desc: The supported encoding type(s) for an EntryPoint request.

httpMethod.desc: An HTTP method that specifies the appropriate HTTP method for a request to an HTTP EntryPoint. Values are capitalized strings as used in HTTP.

urlTemplate.desc: An url template (RFC6570) that will be used to construct the target of the execution of the action.

http://schema.org/Enumeration.desc: Lists or enumerations—for example, a list of cuisines or music genres, etc.

supersededBy.desc: Relates a term (i.e. a property, class or enumeration) to one that supersedes it.

http://schema.org/Episode.desc: A media episode (e.g. TV, radio, video game) which can be part of a series or season.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episodeNumber.desc: Position of the episode within an ordered group of episodes.

partOfSeason.desc: The season to which this episode belongs.

partOfSeries.desc: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/Event.desc: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the 'offers' property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

attendee.desc: A person or organization attending the event.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

endDate.desc: The end date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

eventStatus.desc: An eventStatus of an event represents its status; particularly useful when an event is cancelled or rescheduled.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the IETF BCP 47 standard.

location.desc: The location of the event, organization or action.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, or give away tickets to an event.

performer.desc: A performer at the event—for example, a presenter, musician, musical group or actor.

performers.desc: The main performer or performers of the event—for example, a presenter, musician, or actor.

previousStartDate.desc: Used in conjunction with eventStatus for rescheduled or cancelled events. This property contains the previously scheduled start date. For rescheduled events, the startDate property should be used for the newly scheduled start date. In the (rare) case of an event that has been postponed and rescheduled multiple times, this field may be repeated.

recordedIn.desc: The CreativeWork that captured all or part of this Event.

startDate.desc: The start date and time of the item (in ISO 8601 date format).

subEvent.desc: An Event that is part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each of which is a subEvent of the conference.

subEvents.desc: Events that are a part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each subEvents of the conference.

superEvent.desc: An event that this event is a part of. For example, a collection of individual music performances might each have a music festival as their superEvent.

typicalAgeRange.desc: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

workPerformed.desc: A work performed in some event, for example a play performed in a TheaterEvent.

http://schema.org/EventReservation.desc: A reservation for an event like a concert, sporting event, or lecture.Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use http://schema.org/Offer.

http://schema.org/EventStatusType.desc: EventStatusType is an enumeration type whose instances represent several states that an Event may be in.

http://schema.org/ExerciseAction.desc: The act of participating in exertive activity for the purposes of improving health and fitness.

course.desc: A sub property of location. The course where this action was taken.

diet.desc: A sub property of instrument. The diet used in this action.

distance.desc: The distance travelled, e.g. exercising or travelling.

exerciseCourse.desc: A sub property of location. The course where this action was taken.

exercisePlan.desc: A sub property of instrument. The exercise plan used on this action.

exerciseRelatedDiet.desc: A sub property of instrument. The diet used in this action.

exerciseType.desc: Type(s) of exercise or activity, such as strength training, flexibility training, aerobics, cardiac rehabilitation, etc.

fromLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

opponent.desc: A sub property of participant. The opponent on this action.

sportsActivityLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The sports activity location where this action occurred.

sportsEvent.desc: A sub property of location. The sports event where this action occurred.

sportsTeam.desc: A sub property of participant. The sports team that participated on this action.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

http://schema.org/ExercisePlan.desc: Fitness-related activity designed for a specific health-related purpose, including defined exercise routines as well as activity prescribed by a clinician.

activityDuration.desc: Length of time to engage in the activity.

activityFrequency.desc: How often one should engage in the activity.

additionalVariable.desc: Any additional component of the exercise prescription that may need to be articulated to the patient. This may include the order of exercises, the number of repetitions of movement, quantitative distance, progressions over time, etc.

exerciseType.desc: Type(s) of exercise or activity, such as strength training, flexibility training, aerobics, cardiac rehabilitation, etc.

intensity.desc: Quantitative measure gauging the degree of force involved in the exercise, for example, heartbeats per minute. May include the velocity of the movement.

repetitions.desc: Number of times one should repeat the activity.

restPeriods.desc: How often one should break from the activity.

workload.desc: Quantitative measure of the physiologic output of the exercise; also referred to as energy expenditure.

http://schema.org/FilmAction.desc: The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.

http://schema.org/FindAction.desc: The act of finding an object..

arrivalAirport.desc: The airport where the flight terminates.

arrivalGate.desc: Identifier of the flight's arrival gate.

arrivalTerminal.desc: Identifier of the flight's arrival terminal.

boardingPolicy.desc: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

carrier.desc: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

departureAirport.desc: The airport where the flight originates.

departureGate.desc: Identifier of the flight's departure gate.

departureTerminal.desc: Identifier of the flight's departure terminal.

estimatedFlightDuration.desc: The estimated time the flight will take.

flightNumber.desc: The unique identifier for a flight including the airline IATA code. For example, if describing United flight 110, where the IATA code for United is 'UA', the flightNumber is 'UA110'.

mealService.desc: Description of the meals that will be provided or available for purchase.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

webCheckinTime.desc: The time when a passenger can check into the flight online.

http://schema.org/FlightReservation.desc: A reservation for air travel.Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use http://schema.org/Offer.

boardingGroup.desc: The airline-specific indicator of boarding order / preference.

passengerPriorityStatus.desc: The priority status assigned to a passenger for security or boarding (e.g. FastTrack or Priority).

passengerSequenceNumber.desc: The passenger's sequence number as assigned by the airline.

securityScreening.desc: The type of security screening the passenger is subject to.

http://schema.org/FollowAction.desc: The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from..

followee.desc: A sub property of object. The person or organization being followed.

acceptsReservations.desc: Indicates whether a FoodEstablishment accepts reservations. Values can be Boolean, an URL at which reservations can be made or (for backwards compatibility) the strings Yes or No.

menu.desc: Either the actual menu or a URL of the menu.

http://schema.org/FoodEstablishmentReser.desc: A reservation to dine at a food-related business.Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

endTime.desc:
The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*.

Note that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

partySize.desc: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.

startTime.desc:
The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December.

Note that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

http://schema.org/Game.desc: The Game type represents things which are games. These are typically rule-governed recreational activities, e.g. role-playing games in which players assume the role of characters in a fictional setting. See also open issues list.

characterAttribute.desc: A piece of data that represents a particular aspect of a fictional character (skill, power, character points, advantage, disadvantage).

gameItem.desc: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

gameLocation.desc: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

numberOfPlayers.desc: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

quest.desc: The task that a player-controlled character, or group of characters may complete in order to gain a reward.

http://schema.org/GamePlayMode.desc: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.

http://schema.org/GameServer.desc: Server that provides game interaction in a multiplayer game.

game.desc: Video game which is played on this server.

playersOnline.desc: Number of players on the server.

http://schema.org/GeoCoordinates.desc: The geographic coordinates of a place or event.

latitude.desc: The latitude of a location. For example 37.42242.

longitude.desc: The longitude of a location. For example -122.08585.

http://schema.org/GeoShape.desc: The geographic shape of a place. A GeoShape can be described using several properties whose values are based on latitude/longitude pairs. Either whitespace or commas can be used to separate latitude and longitude; whitespace should be used when writing a list of several such points.

box.desc: A box is the area enclosed by the rectangle formed by two points. The first point is the lower corner, the second point is the upper corner. A box is expressed as two points separated by a space character.

circle.desc: A circle is the circular region of a specified radius centered at a specified latitude and longitude. A circle is expressed as a pair followed by a radius in meters.

line.desc: A line is a point-to-point path consisting of two or more points. A line is expressed as a series of two or more point objects separated by space.

polygon.desc: A polygon is the area enclosed by a point-to-point path for which the starting and ending points are the same. A polygon is expressed as a series of four or more space delimited points where the first and final points are identical.

http://schema.org/GiveAction.desc: The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction..

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/GovernmentOffice.desc: A government office—for example, an IRS or DMV office.

http://schema.org/GovernmentPermit.desc: A permit issued by a government agency.

http://schema.org/GovernmentService.desc: A service provided by a government organization, e.g. food stamps, veterans benefits, etc.

serviceOperator.desc: The operating organization, if different from the provider.  This enables the representation of services that are provided by an organization, but operated by another organization like a subcontractor.

http://schema.org/HVACBusiness.desc: A business that provide Heating, Ventilation and Air Conditioning services.

http://schema.org/HobbyShop.desc: A store that sells materials useful or necessary for various hobbies.

availableService.desc: A medical service available from this provider.

medicalSpecialty.desc: A medical specialty of the provider.

http://schema.org/Hostel.desc: A hostel - cheap accommodation, often in shared dormitories.

http://schema.org/IgnoreAction.desc: The act of intentionally disregarding the object. An agent ignores an object.

http://schema.org/ImageGallery.desc: Web page type: Image gallery page.

representativeOfPage.desc: Indicates whether this image is representative of the content of the page.

thumbnail.desc: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

http://schema.org/ImagingTest.desc: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes.

http://schema.org/IndividualProduct.desc: A single, identifiable product instance (e.g. a laptop with a particular serial number).

serialNumber.desc: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

http://schema.org/InfectiousAgentClass.desc: Classes of agents or pathogens that transmit infectious diseases. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/InfectiousDisease.desc: An infectious disease is a clinically evident human disease resulting from the presence of pathogenic microbial agents, like pathogenic viruses, pathogenic bacteria, fungi, protozoa, multicellular parasites, and prions. To be considered an infectious disease, such pathogens are known to be able to cause this disease.

infectiousAgent.desc: The actual infectious agent, such as a specific bacterium.

infectiousAgentClass.desc: The class of infectious agent (bacteria, prion, etc.) that causes the disease.

transmissionMethod.desc: How the disease spreads, either as a route or vector, for example 'direct contact', 'Aedes aegypti', etc.

http://schema.org/InformAction.desc: The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/InsertAction.desc: The act of adding at a specific location in an ordered collection.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

http://schema.org/InstallAction.desc: The act of installing an application.

http://schema.org/Intangible.desc: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things such as quantities, structured values, etc.

http://schema.org/InteractAction.desc: The act of interacting with another person or organization.

http://schema.org/InviteAction.desc: The act of asking someone to attend an event. Reciprocal of RsvpAction.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/Invoice.desc: A statement of the money due for goods or services; a bill.

accountId.desc: The identifier for the account the payment will be applied to.

billingPeriod.desc: The time interval used to compute the invoice.

broker.desc: An entity that arranges for an exchange between a buyer and a seller.  In most cases a broker never acquires or releases ownership of a product or service involved in an exchange.  If it is not clear whether an entity is a broker, seller, or buyer, the latter two terms are preferred.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.
