confirmationNumber.desc: A number that confirms the given order or payment has been received.

customer.desc: Party placing the order or paying the invoice.

minimumPaymentDue.desc: The minimum payment required at this time.

paymentDue.desc: The date that payment is due.

paymentMethod.desc: The name of the credit card or other method of payment for the order.

paymentMethodId.desc: An identifier for the method of payment used (e.g. the last 4 digits of the credit card).

paymentStatus.desc: The status of payment; whether the invoice has been paid or not.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

referencesOrder.desc: The Order(s) related to this Invoice. One or more Orders may be combined into a single Invoice.

scheduledPaymentDate.desc: The date the invoice is scheduled to be paid.

http://schema.org/ItemAvailability.desc: A list of possible product availability options.

http://schema.org/ItemList.desc: A list of items of any sort—for example, Top 10 Movies About Weathermen, or Top 100 Party Songs. Not to be confused with HTML lists, which are often used only for formatting.

itemListElement.desc:
For itemListElement values, you can use simple strings (e.g. "Peter", "Paul", "Mary"), existing entities, or use ListItem.
    
    Text values are best if the elements in the list are plain strings. Existing entities are best for a simple, unordered list of existing things in your data. ListItem is used with ordered lists when you want to provide additional context about the element in that list or when the same item might be in different places in different lists.
    
    Note: The order of elements in your mark-up is not sufficient for indicating the order or elements.  Use ListItem with a 'position' property in such cases.

itemListOrder.desc: Type of ordering (e.g. Ascending, Descending, Unordered).

numberOfItems.desc: The number of items in an ItemList. Note that some descriptions might not fully describe all items in a list (e.g., multi-page pagination); in such cases, the numberOfItems would be for the entire list.

http://schema.org/ItemListOrderType.desc: Enumerated for values for itemListOrder for indicating how an ordered ItemList is organized.

http://schema.org/ItemPage.desc: A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.

http://schema.org/JobPosting.desc: A listing that describes a job opening in a certain organization.

baseSalary.desc: The base salary of the job or of an employee in an EmployeeRole.

benefits.desc: Description of benefits associated with the job.

datePosted.desc: Publication date for the job posting.

educationRequirements.desc: Educational background needed for the position.

employmentType.desc: Type of employment (e.g. full-time, part-time, contract, temporary, seasonal, internship).

experienceRequirements.desc: Description of skills and experience needed for the position.

incentiveCompensation.desc: Description of bonus and commission compensation aspects of the job.

incentives.desc: Description of bonus and commission compensation aspects of the job.

industry.desc: The industry associated with the job position.

jobBenefits.desc: Description of benefits associated with the job.

jobLocation.desc: A (typically single) geographic location associated with the job position.

occupationalCategory.desc: Category or categories describing the job. Use BLS O*NET-SOC taxonomy: http://www.onetcenter.org/taxonomy.html. Ideally includes textual label and formal code, with the property repeated for each applicable value.

qualifications.desc: Specific qualifications required for this role.

salaryCurrency.desc: The currency (coded using ISO 4217, http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217 ) used for the main salary information in this job posting or for this employee.

skills.desc: Skills required to fulfill this role.

specialCommitments.desc: Any special commitments associated with this job posting. Valid entries include VeteranCommit, MilitarySpouseCommit, etc.

workHours.desc: The typical working hours for this job (e.g. 1st shift, night shift, 8am-5pm).

http://schema.org/JoinAction.desc: An agent joins an event/group with participants/friends at a location..

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/Joint.desc: The anatomical location at which two or more bones make contact.

biomechnicalClass.desc: The biomechanical properties of the bone.

functionalClass.desc: The degree of mobility the joint allows.

structuralClass.desc: The name given to how bone physically connects to each other.

http://schema.org/Landform.desc: A landform or physical feature.  Landform elements include mountains, plains, lakes, rivers, seascape and oceanic waterbody interface features such as bays, peninsulas, seas and so forth, including sub-aqueous terrain features such as submersed mountain ranges, volcanoes, and the great ocean basins.

http://schema.org/Language.desc: Natural languages such as Spanish, Tamil, Hindi, English, etc. and programming languages such as Scheme and Lisp.

http://schema.org/LeaveAction.desc: An agent leaves an event / group with participants/friends at a location..

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

http://schema.org/LegislativeBuilding.desc: A legislative building—for example, the state capitol.

http://schema.org/LendAction.desc: The act of providing an object under an agreement that it will be returned at a later date. Reciprocal of BorrowAction..

borrower.desc: A sub property of participant. The person that borrows the object being lent.

http://schema.org/LifestyleModification.desc: A process of care involving exercise, changes to diet, fitness routines, and other lifestyle changes aimed at improving a health condition.

http://schema.org/Ligament.desc: A short band of tough, flexible, fibrous connective tissue that functions to connect multiple bones, cartilages, and structurally support joints.

http://schema.org/LikeAction.desc: The act of expressing a positive sentiment about the object. An agent likes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

http://schema.org/LiquorStore.desc: A shop that sells alcoholic drinks such as wine, beer, whisky and other spirits.

http://schema.org/ListItem.desc: An list item, e.g. a step in a checklist or how-to description.

item.desc: An entity represented by an entry in a list (e.g. an 'artist' in a list of 'artists')’.

nextItem.desc: A link to the ListItem that follows the current one.

position.desc: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

previousItem.desc: A link to the ListItem that preceeds the current one.

http://schema.org/ListenAction.desc: The act of consuming audio content.

http://schema.org/LocalBusiness.desc: A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.

branchOf.desc: The larger organization that this local business is a branch of, if any.

currenciesAccepted.desc: The currency accepted (in ISO 4217 currency format).

openingHours.desc: The opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'.- Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: Mo, Tu, We, Th, Fr, Sa, Su.- Times are specified using 24:00 time. For example, 3pm is specified as 15:00. - Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. - If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

parentOrganization.desc: The larger organization that this local business is a branch of, if any.

priceRange.desc: The price range of the business, for example $$$.

http://schema.org/LockerDelivery.desc: A DeliveryMethod in which an item is made available via locker.

http://schema.org/LodgingBusiness.desc: A lodging business, such as a motel, hotel, or inn.

http://schema.org/LodgingReservation.desc: A reservation for lodging at a hotel, motel, inn, etc.Note: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

checkinTime.desc: The earliest someone may check into a lodging establishment.

checkoutTime.desc: The latest someone may check out of a lodging establishment.

lodgingUnitDescription.desc: A full description of the lodging unit.

lodgingUnitType.desc: Textual description of the unit type (including suite vs. room, size of bed, etc.).

numAdults.desc: The number of adults staying in the unit.

numChildren.desc: The number of children staying in the unit.

http://schema.org/LoseAction.desc: The act of being defeated in a competitive activity.

winner.desc: A sub property of participant. The winner of the action.

http://schema.org/LymphaticVessel.desc: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries lymph fluid unidirectionally toward the heart.

originatesFrom.desc: The vasculature the lymphatic structure originates, or afferents, from.

regionDrained.desc: The anatomical or organ system drained by this vessel; generally refers to a specific part of an organ.

runsTo.desc: The vasculature the lymphatic structure runs, or efferents, to.

mapType.desc: Indicates the kind of Map, from the MapCategoryType Enumeration.

http://schema.org/MapCategoryType.desc: An enumeration of several kinds of Map.

http://schema.org/MarryAction.desc: The act of marrying a person.

http://schema.org/Mass.desc: Properties that take Mass as values are of the form '<Number> <Mass unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 kg'.

http://schema.org/MaximumDoseSchedule.desc: The maximum dosing schedule considered safe for a drug or supplement as recommended by an authority or by the drug/supplement's manufacturer. Capture the recommending authority in the recognizingAuthority property of MedicalEntity.

http://schema.org/MediaObject.desc: An image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).

associatedArticle.desc: A NewsArticle associated with the Media Object.

bitrate.desc: The bitrate of the media object.

contentUrl.desc: Actual bytes of the media object, for example the image file or video file.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

embedUrl.desc: A URL pointing to a player for a specific video. In general, this is the information in the src element of an embed tag and should not be the same as the content of the loc tag.

encodesCreativeWork.desc: The CreativeWork encoded by this media object.

expires.desc: Date the content expires and is no longer useful or available. Useful for videos.

playerType.desc: Player type required—for example, Flash or Silverlight.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

regionsAllowed.desc: The regions where the media is allowed. If not specified, then it's assumed to be allowed everywhere. Specify the countries in ISO 3166 format.

requiresSubscription.desc: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are true or false (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

uploadDate.desc: Date when this media object was uploaded to this site.

http://schema.org/MedicalAudience.desc: Target audiences for medical web pages. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalCause.desc: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

causeOf.desc: The condition, complication, symptom, sign, etc. caused.

availableService.desc: A medical service available from this provider.

medicalSpecialty.desc: A medical specialty of the provider.

http://schema.org/MedicalCode.desc: A code for a medical entity.

http://schema.org/MedicalCondition.desc: Any condition of the human body that affects the normal functioning of a person, whether physically or mentally. Includes diseases, injuries, disabilities, disorders, syndromes, etc.

associatedAnatomy.desc: The anatomy of the underlying organ system or structures associated with this entity.

cause.desc: An underlying cause. More specifically, one of the causative agent(s) that are most directly responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in the occurrence.

differentialDiagnosis.desc: One of a set of differential diagnoses for the condition. Specifically, a closely-related or competing diagnosis typically considered later in the cognitive process whereby this medical condition is distinguished from others most likely responsible for a similar collection of signs and symptoms to reach the most parsimonious diagnosis or diagnoses in a patient.

epidemiology.desc: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

expectedPrognosis.desc: The likely outcome in either the short term or long term of the medical condition.

naturalProgression.desc: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.

pathophysiology.desc: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

possibleComplication.desc: A possible unexpected and unfavorable evolution of a medical condition. Complications may include worsening of the signs or symptoms of the disease, extension of the condition to other organ systems, etc.

possibleTreatment.desc: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

primaryPrevention.desc: A preventative therapy used to prevent an initial occurrence of the medical condition, such as vaccination.

riskFactor.desc: A modifiable or non-modifiable factor that increases the risk of a patient contracting this condition, e.g. age,  coexisting condition.

secondaryPrevention.desc: A preventative therapy used to prevent reoccurrence of the medical condition after an initial episode of the condition.

signOrSymptom.desc: A sign or symptom of this condition. Signs are objective or physically observable manifestations of the medical condition while symptoms are the subjective experience of the medical condition.

stage.desc: The stage of the condition, if applicable.

subtype.desc: A more specific type of the condition, where applicable, for example 'Type 1 Diabetes', 'Type 2 Diabetes', or 'Gestational Diabetes' for Diabetes.

typicalTest.desc: A medical test typically performed given this condition.

http://schema.org/MedicalConditionStage.desc: A stage of a medical condition, such as 'Stage IIIa'.

stageAsNumber.desc: The stage represented as a number, e.g. 3.

subStageSuffix.desc: The substage, e.g. 'a' for Stage IIIa.

http://schema.org/MedicalContraindicatio.desc: A condition or factor that serves as a reason to withhold a certain medical therapy. Contraindications can be absolute (there are no reasonable circumstances for undertaking a course of action) or relative (the patient is at higher risk of complications, but that these risks may be outweighed by other considerations or mitigated by other measures).

http://schema.org/MedicalDevice.desc: Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.

adverseOutcome.desc: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

indication.desc: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

postOp.desc: A description of the postoperative procedures, care, and/or followups for this device.

preOp.desc: A description of the workup, testing, and other preparations required before implanting this device.

procedure.desc: A description of the procedure involved in setting up, using, and/or installing the device.

purpose.desc: A goal towards an action is taken. Can be concrete or abstract.

seriousAdverseOutcome.desc: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

http://schema.org/MedicalDevicePurpose.desc: Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.

http://schema.org/MedicalEntity.desc: The most generic type of entity related to health and the practice of medicine.

code.desc: A medical code for the entity, taken from a controlled vocabulary or ontology such as ICD-9, DiseasesDB, MeSH, SNOMED-CT, RxNorm, etc.

guideline.desc: A medical guideline related to this entity.

medicineSystem.desc: The system of medicine that includes this MedicalEntity, for example 'evidence-based', 'homeopathic', 'chiropractic', etc.

recognizingAuthority.desc: If applicable, the organization that officially recognizes this entity as part of its endorsed system of medicine.

relevantSpecialty.desc: If applicable, a medical specialty in which this entity is relevant.

study.desc: A medical study or trial related to this entity.

http://schema.org/MedicalEnumeration.desc: Enumerations related to health and the practice of medicine.

http://schema.org/MedicalEvidenceLevel.desc: Level of evidence for a medical guideline. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalGuideline.desc: Any recommendation made by a standard society (e.g. ACC/AHA) or consensus statement that denotes how to diagnose and treat a particular condition. Note: this type should be used to tag the actual guideline recommendation; if the guideline recommendation occurs in a larger scholarly article, use MedicalScholarlyArticle to tag the overall article, not this type. Note also: the organization making the recommendation should be captured in the recognizingAuthority base property of MedicalEntity.

evidenceLevel.desc: Strength of evidence of the data used to formulate the guideline (enumerated).

evidenceOrigin.desc: Source of the data used to formulate the guidance, e.g. RCT, consensus opinion, etc.

guidelineDate.desc: Date on which this guideline's recommendation was made.

guidelineSubject.desc: The medical conditions, treatments, etc. that are the subject of the guideline.

http://schema.org/MedicalGuidelineContra.desc: A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.

http://schema.org/MedicalGuidelineRecomm.desc: A guideline recommendation that is regarded as efficacious and where quality of the data supporting the recommendation is sound.

recommendationStrength.desc: Strength of the guideline's recommendation (e.g. 'class I').

http://schema.org/MedicalImagingTechniqu.desc: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalIndication.desc: A condition or factor that indicates use of a medical therapy, including signs, symptoms, risk factors, anatomical states, etc.

http://schema.org/MedicalIntangible.desc: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.

http://schema.org/MedicalObservationalSt.desc: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

studyDesign.desc: Specifics about the observational study design (enumerated).

http://schema.org/MedicalObservationalSt.desc: Design models for observational medical studies. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalOrganization.desc: A medical organization, such as a doctor's office or clinic.

http://schema.org/MedicalProcedure.desc: A process of care used in either a diagnostic, therapeutic, or palliative capacity that relies on invasive (surgical), non-invasive, or percutaneous techniques.

followup.desc: Typical or recommended followup care after the procedure is performed.

preparation.desc: Typical preparation that a patient must undergo before having the procedure performed.

procedureType.desc: The type of procedure, for example Surgical, Noninvasive, or Percutaneous.

http://schema.org/MedicalProcedureType.desc: An enumeration that describes different types of medical procedures.

http://schema.org/MedicalRiskCalculator.desc: A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.

http://schema.org/MedicalRiskEstimator.desc: Any rule set or interactive tool for estimating the risk of developing a complication or condition.

estimatesRiskOf.desc: The condition, complication, or symptom whose risk is being estimated.

includedRiskFactor.desc: A modifiable or non-modifiable risk factor included in the calculation, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

http://schema.org/MedicalRiskFactor.desc: A risk factor is anything that increases a person's likelihood of developing or contracting a disease, medical condition, or complication.

increasesRiskOf.desc: The condition, complication, etc. influenced by this factor.

http://schema.org/MedicalRiskScore.desc: A simple system that adds up the number of risk factors to yield a score that is associated with prognosis, e.g. CHAD score, TIMI risk score.

algorithm.desc: The algorithm or rules to follow to compute the score.

http://schema.org/MedicalScholarlyArticl.desc: A scholarly article in the medical domain.

publicationType.desc: The type of the medical article, taken from the US NLM MeSH publication type catalog.

http://schema.org/MedicalSign.desc: Any physical manifestation of a person's medical condition discoverable by objective diagnostic tests or physical examination.

identifyingExam.desc: A physical examination that can identify this sign.

identifyingTest.desc: A diagnostic test that can identify this sign.

http://schema.org/MedicalSignOrSymptom.desc: Any indication of the existence of a medical condition or disease.

cause.desc: An underlying cause. More specifically, one of the causative agent(s) that are most directly responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in the occurrence.

possibleTreatment.desc: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

http://schema.org/MedicalSpecialty.desc: Any specific branch of medical science or practice. Medical specialities include clinical specialties that pertain to particular organ systems and their respective disease states, as well as allied health specialties. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalStudy.desc: A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. Note: use the code property of MedicalEntity to store study IDs, e.g. clinicaltrials.gov ID.

outcome.desc: Expected or actual outcomes of the study.

population.desc: Any characteristics of the population used in the study, e.g. 'males under 65'.

studyLocation.desc: The location in which the study is taking/took place.

studySubject.desc: A subject of the study, i.e. one of the medical conditions, therapies, devices, drugs, etc. investigated by the study.

http://schema.org/MedicalStudyStatus.desc: The status of a medical study. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalSymptom.desc: Any indication of the existence of a medical condition or disease that is apparent to the patient.

http://schema.org/MedicalTest.desc: Any medical test, typically performed for diagnostic purposes.

affectedBy.desc: Drugs that affect the test's results.

normalRange.desc: Range of acceptable values for a typical patient, when applicable.

signDetected.desc: A sign detected by the test.

usedToDiagnose.desc: A condition the test is used to diagnose.

usesDevice.desc: Device used to perform the test.

http://schema.org/MedicalTestPanel.desc: Any collection of tests commonly ordered together.

subTest.desc: A component test of the panel.

http://schema.org/MedicalTherapy.desc: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

adverseOutcome.desc: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

duplicateTherapy.desc: A therapy that duplicates or overlaps this one.

indication.desc: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

seriousAdverseOutcome.desc: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

http://schema.org/MedicalTrial.desc: A medical trial is a type of medical study that uses scientific process used to compare the safety and efficacy of medical therapies or medical procedures. In general, medical trials are controlled and subjects are allocated at random to the different treatment and/or control groups.

http://schema.org/MedicalTrialDesign.desc: Design models for medical trials. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/MedicalWebPage.desc: A web page that provides medical information.

aspect.desc: An aspect of medical practice that is considered on the page, such as 'diagnosis', 'treatment', 'causes', 'prognosis', 'etiology', 'epidemiology', etc.

http://schema.org/MiddleSchool.desc: A middle school (typically for children aged around 11-14, although this varies somewhat).

http://schema.org/MobileApplication.desc: A software application designed specifically to work well on a mobile device such as a telephone.

carrierRequirements.desc: Specifies specific carrier(s) requirements for the application (e.g. an application may only work on a specific carrier network).

http://schema.org/MobilePhoneStore.desc: A store that sells mobile phones and related accessories.

http://schema.org/Mountain.desc: A mountain, like Mount Whitney or Mount Everest.

http://schema.org/MoveAction.desc: The act of an agent relocating to a place..

fromLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

toLocation.desc: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

subtitleLanguage.desc: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in IETF BCP 47 standard format.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/MovieClip.desc: A short segment/part of a movie.

http://schema.org/MovieSeries.desc: A series of movies. Included movies can be indicated with the hasPart property.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

screenCount.desc: The number of screens in the movie theater.

http://schema.org/Muscle.desc: A muscle is an anatomical structure consisting of a contractile form of tissue that animals use to effect movement.

antagonist.desc: The muscle whose action counteracts the specified muscle.

bloodSupply.desc: The blood vessel that carries blood from the heart to the muscle.

insertion.desc: The place of attachment of a muscle, or what the muscle moves.

nerve.desc: The underlying innervation associated with the muscle.

origin.desc: The place or point where a muscle arises.

albumProductionType.desc: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

albumReleaseType.desc: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

byArtist.desc: The artist that performed this album or recording.

http://schema.org/MusicAlbumProductionTy.desc: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

http://schema.org/MusicAlbumReleaseType.desc: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

composer.desc: The person or organization who wrote the composition.

firstPerformance.desc: The date and place the work was first performed.

includedComposition.desc: Smaller compositions included in this work (e.g. a movement in a symphony).

iswcCode.desc: The International Standard Musical Work Code for the composition.

lyricist.desc: The person who wrote the words.

musicArrangement.desc: An arrangement derived from the composition.

musicCompositionForm.desc: The type of composition (e.g. overture, sonata, symphony, etc.).

musicalKey.desc: The key, mode, or scale this composition uses.

recordedAs.desc: An audio recording of the work.

http://schema.org/MusicGroup.desc: A musical group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a choir. Can also be a solo musician.

genre.desc: Genre of the creative work or group.

musicGroupMember.desc: A member of a music group—for example, John, Paul, George, or Ringo.

track.desc: A music recording (track)—usually a single song. If an ItemList is given, the list should contain items of type MusicRecording.

tracks.desc: A music recording (track)—usually a single song.

http://schema.org/MusicPlaylist.desc: A collection of music tracks in playlist form.

numTracks.desc: The number of tracks in this album or playlist.

track.desc: A music recording (track)—usually a single song. If an ItemList is given, the list should contain items of type MusicRecording.

tracks.desc: A music recording (track)—usually a single song.

http://schema.org/MusicRecording.desc: A music recording (track), usually a single song.

byArtist.desc: The artist that performed this album or recording.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

inAlbum.desc: The album to which this recording belongs.

inPlaylist.desc: The playlist to which this recording belongs.

isrcCode.desc: The International Standard Recording Code for the recording.

recordingOf.desc: The composition this track is a recording of.

http://schema.org/MusicRelease.desc: A MusicRelease is a specific release of a music album.

catalogNumber.desc: The catalog number for the release.

creditedTo.desc: The group the release is credited to if different than the byArtist. For example, Red and Blue is credited to "Stefani Germanotta Band", but by Lady Gaga.

duration.desc: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

musicReleaseFormat.desc: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).

recordLabel.desc: The label that issued the release.

releaseOf.desc: The album this is a release of.

http://schema.org/MusicReleaseFormatType.desc: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).

http://schema.org/Nerve.desc: A common pathway for the electrochemical nerve impulses that are transmitted along each of the axons.

branch.desc: The branches that delineate from the nerve bundle.

nerveMotor.desc: The neurological pathway extension that involves muscle control.

sensoryUnit.desc: The neurological pathway extension that inputs and sends information to the brain or spinal cord.

sourcedFrom.desc: The neurological pathway that originates the neurons.

dateline.desc: The location where the NewsArticle was produced.

printColumn.desc: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.

printEdition.desc: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.

printPage.desc: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).

printSection.desc: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.

carbohydrateContent.desc: The number of grams of carbohydrates.

cholesterolContent.desc: The number of milligrams of cholesterol.

fatContent.desc: The number of grams of fat.

fiberContent.desc: The number of grams of fiber.

proteinContent.desc: The number of grams of protein.

saturatedFatContent.desc: The number of grams of saturated fat.

servingSize.desc: The serving size, in terms of the number of volume or mass.

sodiumContent.desc: The number of milligrams of sodium.

sugarContent.desc: The number of grams of sugar.

transFatContent.desc: The number of grams of trans fat.

unsaturatedFatContent.desc: The number of grams of unsaturated fat.

http://schema.org/Offer.desc:
An offer to transfer some rights to an item or to provide a service—for example, an offer to sell tickets to an event, to rent the DVD of a movie, to stream a TV show over the internet, to repair a motorcycle, or to loan a book.
      
      For GTIN-related fields, see
      Check Digit calculator
      and validation guide
      from GS1.

acceptedPaymentMethod.desc: The payment method(s) accepted by seller for this offer.

addOn.desc: An additional offer that can only be obtained in combination with the first base offer (e.g. supplements and extensions that are available for a surcharge).

advanceBookingRequirement.desc: The amount of time that is required between accepting the offer and the actual usage of the resource or service.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

availability.desc: The availability of this item—for example In stock, Out of stock, Pre-order, etc.

availabilityEnds.desc: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availabilityStarts.desc: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

availableAtOrFrom.desc: The place(s) from which the offer can be obtained (e.g. store locations).

availableDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) available for this offer.

businessFunction.desc: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

deliveryLeadTime.desc: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods leaving the warehouse.

eligibleCustomerType.desc: The type(s) of customers for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleDuration.desc: The duration for which the given offer is valid.

eligibleQuantity.desc: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

eligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.

eligibleTransactionVolume.desc: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

gtin12.desc: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin13.desc: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin14.desc: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin8.desc: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

includesObject.desc: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in the offer.

ineligibleRegion.desc: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.

inventoryLevel.desc: The current approximate inventory level for the item or items.

itemCondition.desc: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

mpn.desc: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

price.desc:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.


      Usage guidelines:


Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of
      including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value.


      Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.


      Note that both RDFa and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values
      alongside more human-friendly formatting.


      Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the price or a price component, when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

priceSpecification.desc: One or more detailed price specifications, indicating the unit price and delivery or payment charges.

priceValidUntil.desc: The date after which the price is no longer available.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

serialNumber.desc: The serial number or any alphanumeric identifier of a particular product. When attached to an offer, it is a shortcut for the serial number of the product included in the offer.

sku.desc: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The end of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

warranty.desc: The warranty promise(s) included in the offer.

http://schema.org/OfferItemCondition.desc: A list of possible conditions for the item.

http://schema.org/OnDemandEvent.desc: A publication event e.g. catch-up TV or radio podcast, during which a program is available on-demand.

http://schema.org/OpeningHoursSpecificat.desc: A structured value providing information about the opening hours of a place or a certain service inside a place.

closes.desc: The closing hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.

dayOfWeek.desc: The day of the week for which these opening hours are valid.

opens.desc: The opening hour of the place or service on the given day(s) of the week.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The end of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

http://schema.org/Optician.desc: A store that sells reading glasses and similar devices for improving vision.

http://schema.org/Order.desc: An order is a confirmation of a transaction (a receipt), which can contain multiple line items, each represented by an Offer that has been accepted by the customer.

acceptedOffer.desc: The offer(s) -- e.g., product, quantity and price combinations -- included in the order.

billingAddress.desc: The billing address for the order.

broker.desc: An entity that arranges for an exchange between a buyer and a seller.  In most cases a broker never acquires or releases ownership of a product or service involved in an exchange.  If it is not clear whether an entity is a broker, seller, or buyer, the latter two terms are preferred.

confirmationNumber.desc: A number that confirms the given order or payment has been received.

customer.desc: Party placing the order or paying the invoice.

discountCode.desc: Code used to redeem a discount.

discountCurrency.desc: The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the discount.

isGift.desc: Was the offer accepted as a gift for someone other than the buyer.

orderDelivery.desc: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.

orderStatus.desc: The current status of the order.

partOfInvoice.desc: The order is being paid as part of the referenced Invoice.

paymentDue.desc: The date that payment is due.

paymentMethod.desc: The name of the credit card or other method of payment for the order.

paymentMethodId.desc: An identifier for the method of payment used (e.g. the last 4 digits of the credit card).

paymentUrl.desc: The URL for sending a payment.

seller.desc: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

http://schema.org/OrderAction.desc: An agent orders an object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

deliveryMethod.desc: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

http://schema.org/OrderItem.desc: An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.

orderDelivery.desc: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.

orderItemNumber.desc: The identifier of the order item.

orderItemStatus.desc: The current status of the order item.

orderQuantity.desc: The number of the item ordered. If the property is not set, assume the quantity is one.

http://schema.org/Organization.desc: An organization such as a school, NGO, corporation, club, etc.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

contactPoint.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

contactPoints.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

department.desc: A relationship between an organization and a department of that organization, also described as an organization (allowing different urls, logos, opening hours). For example: a store with a pharmacy, or a bakery with a cafe.

dissolutionDate.desc: The date that this organization was dissolved.

duns.desc: The Dun & Bradstreet DUNS number for identifying an organization or business person.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

events.desc: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

founder.desc: A person who founded this organization.

founders.desc: A person who founded this organization.

foundingDate.desc: The date that this organization was founded.

foundingLocation.desc: The place where the Organization was founded.

globalLocationNumber.desc: The Global Location Number (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

hasPOS.desc: Points-of-Sales operated by the organization or person.

isicV4.desc: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

legalName.desc: The official name of the organization, e.g. the registered company name.

location.desc: The location of the event, organization or action.

makesOffer.desc: A pointer to products or services offered by the organization or person.

member.desc: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

memberOf.desc: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.

naics.desc: The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for a particular organization or business person.

numberOfEmployees.desc: The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.

owns.desc: Products owned by the organization or person.

seeks.desc: A pointer to products or services sought by the organization or person (demand).

subOrganization.desc: A relationship between two organizations where the first includes the second, e.g., as a subsidiary. See also: the more specific 'department' property.

taxID.desc: The Tax / Fiscal ID of the organization or person, e.g. the TIN in the US or the CIF/NIF in Spain.

vatID.desc: The Value-added Tax ID of the organization or person.

http://schema.org/OrganizationRole.desc: A subclass of Role used to describe roles within organizations.

numberedPosition.desc: A number associated with a role in an organization, for example, the number on an athlete's jersey.

http://schema.org/OrganizeAction.desc: The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.

http://schema.org/OwnershipInfo.desc: A structured value providing information about when a certain organization or person owned a certain product.

acquiredFrom.desc: The organization or person from which the product was acquired.

ownedFrom.desc: The date and time of obtaining the product.

ownedThrough.desc: The date and time of giving up ownership on the product.

typeOfGood.desc: The product that this structured value is referring to.

http://schema.org/PaintAction.desc: The act of producing a painting, typically with paint and canvas as instruments.

http://schema.org/PalliativeProcedure.desc: A medical procedure intended primarily for palliative purposes, aimed at relieving the symptoms of an underlying health condition.

http://schema.org/ParcelDelivery.desc: The delivery of a parcel either via the postal service or a commercial service.

carrier.desc: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

deliveryStatus.desc: New entry added as the package passes through each leg of its journey (from shipment to final delivery).

expectedArrivalFrom.desc: The earliest date the package may arrive.

expectedArrivalUntil.desc: The latest date the package may arrive.

hasDeliveryMethod.desc: Method used for delivery or shipping.

partOfOrder.desc: The overall order the items in this delivery were included in.

provider.desc: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

trackingUrl.desc: Tracking url for the parcel delivery.

http://schema.org/ParcelService.desc:
A private parcel service as the delivery mode available for a certain offer.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DHL 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#FederalExpress 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#UPS

http://schema.org/ParentAudience.desc: A set of characteristics describing parents, who can be interested in viewing some content.

http://schema.org/ParkingFacility.desc: A parking lot or other parking facility.

http://schema.org/PathologyTest.desc: A medical test performed by a laboratory that typically involves examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.

tissueSample.desc: The type of tissue sample required for the test.

http://schema.org/PawnShop.desc: A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.

http://schema.org/PayAction.desc: An agent pays a price to a participant.

purpose.desc: A goal towards an action is taken. Can be concrete or abstract.

recipient.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

http://schema.org/PaymentChargeSpecifica.desc: The costs of settling the payment using a particular payment method.

appliesToDeliveryMethod.desc: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

appliesToPaymentMethod.desc: The payment method(s) to which the payment charge specification applies.

http://schema.org/PaymentMethod.desc:
A payment method is a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase. Payment methods are characterized by the legal and technical structures used, and by the organization or group carrying out the transaction.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#GoogleCheckout 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PayPal 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PaySwarm

http://schema.org/PeopleAudience.desc: A set of characteristics belonging to people, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

healthCondition.desc: Expectations for health conditions of target audience.

requiredGender.desc: Audiences defined by a person's gender.

requiredMaxAge.desc: Audiences defined by a person's maximum age.

requiredMinAge.desc: Audiences defined by a person's minimum age.

suggestedGender.desc: The gender of the person or audience.

suggestedMaxAge.desc: Maximal age recommended for viewing content.

suggestedMinAge.desc: Minimal age recommended for viewing content.

http://schema.org/PerformAction.desc: The act of participating in performance arts.

entertainmentBusiness.desc: A sub property of location. The entertainment business where the action occurred.

http://schema.org/PerformanceRole.desc: A PerformanceRole is a Role that some entity places with regard to a theatrical performance, e.g. in a Movie, TVSeries etc.

characterName.desc: The name of a character played in some acting or performing role, i.e. in a PerformanceRole.

http://schema.org/PerformingArtsTheater.desc: A theater or other performing art center.

http://schema.org/PerformingGroup.desc: A performance group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a circus.

http://schema.org/Periodical.desc:
A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper to continue indefinitely.

      See also blog post.

issn.desc: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this periodical. You can repeat this property to (for example) identify different formats of this periodical.

http://schema.org/Permit.desc: A permit issued by an organization, e.g. a parking pass.

issuedBy.desc: The organization issuing the ticket or permit.

issuedThrough.desc: The service through with the permit was granted.

permitAudience.desc: The target audience for this permit.

validFor.desc: The time validity of the permit.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validIn.desc: The geographic area where the permit is valid.

validUntil.desc: The date when the item is no longer valid.

http://schema.org/Person.desc: A person (alive, dead, undead, or fictional).

additionalName.desc: An additional name for a Person, can be used for a middle name.

affiliation.desc: An organization that this person is affiliated with. For example, a school/university, a club, or a team.

alumniOf.desc: An educational organizations that the person is an alumni of.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

birthPlace.desc: The place where the person was born.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

contactPoint.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

contactPoints.desc: A contact point for a person or organization.

deathPlace.desc: The place where the person died.

duns.desc: The Dun & Bradstreet DUNS number for identifying an organization or business person.

familyName.desc: Family name. In the U.S., the last name of an Person. This can be used along with givenName instead of the name property.

follows.desc: The most generic uni-directional social relation.

givenName.desc: Given name. In the U.S., the first name of a Person. This can be used along with familyName instead of the name property.

globalLocationNumber.desc: The Global Location Number (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

hasPOS.desc: Points-of-Sales operated by the organization or person.

homeLocation.desc: A contact location for a person's residence.

honorificPrefix.desc: An honorific prefix preceding a Person's name such as Dr/Mrs/Mr.

honorificSuffix.desc: An honorific suffix preceding a Person's name such as M.D. /PhD/MSCSW.

isicV4.desc: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

jobTitle.desc: The job title of the person (for example, Financial Manager).

knows.desc: The most generic bi-directional social/work relation.

makesOffer.desc: A pointer to products or services offered by the organization or person.

memberOf.desc: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.

naics.desc: The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for a particular organization or business person.

netWorth.desc: The total financial value of the organization or person as calculated by subtracting assets from liabilities.

owns.desc: Products owned by the organization or person.

performerIn.desc: Event that this person is a performer or participant in.

seeks.desc: A pointer to products or services sought by the organization or person (demand).

taxID.desc: The Tax / Fiscal ID of the organization or person, e.g. the TIN in the US or the CIF/NIF in Spain.

vatID.desc: The Value-added Tax ID of the organization or person.

weight.desc: The weight of the product or person.

workLocation.desc: A contact location for a person's place of work.

worksFor.desc: Organizations that the person works for.

http://schema.org/PhotographAction.desc: The act of capturing still images of objects using a camera.

http://schema.org/PhysicalActivity.desc: Any bodily activity that enhances or maintains physical fitness and overall health and wellness. Includes activity that is part of daily living and routine, structured exercise, and exercise prescribed as part of a medical treatment or recovery plan.

associatedAnatomy.desc: The anatomy of the underlying organ system or structures associated with this entity.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

epidemiology.desc: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

pathophysiology.desc: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

http://schema.org/PhysicalActivityCatego.desc: Categories of physical activity, organized by physiologic classification.

http://schema.org/PhysicalExam.desc: A type of physical examination of a patient performed by a physician. Enumerated type.

http://schema.org/PhysicalTherapy.desc: A process of progressive physical care and rehabilitation aimed at improving a health condition.

availableService.desc: A medical service available from this provider.

hospitalAffiliation.desc: A hospital with which the physician or office is affiliated.

medicalSpecialty.desc: A medical specialty of the provider.

http://schema.org/Place.desc: Entities that have a somewhat fixed, physical extension.

additionalProperty.desc:
A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org. 

Note: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

containedIn.desc: The basic containment relation between places.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

events.desc: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

geo.desc: The geo coordinates of the place.

globalLocationNumber.desc: The Global Location Number (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

hasMap.desc: A URL to a map of the place.

isicV4.desc: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

map.desc: A URL to a map of the place.

maps.desc: A URL to a map of the place.

openingHoursSpecification.desc: The opening hours of a certain place.

http://schema.org/PlaceOfWorship.desc: Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.

http://schema.org/PlanAction.desc: The act of planning the execution of an event/task/action/reservation/plan to a future date.

scheduledTime.desc: The time the object is scheduled to.

http://schema.org/PlayAction.desc: The act of playing/exercising/training/performing for enjoyment, leisure, recreation, Competition or exercise..

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

event.desc: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

addressCountry.desc: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code.

addressLocality.desc: The locality. For example, Mountain View.

postOfficeBoxNumber.desc: The post office box number for PO box addresses.

streetAddress.desc: The street address. For example, 1600 Amphitheatre Pkwy.

http://schema.org/PrependAction.desc: The act of inserting at the beginning if an ordered collection.

http://schema.org/PreventionIndication.desc: An indication for preventing an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

http://schema.org/PriceSpecification.desc: A structured value representing a monetary amount. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup.

eligibleQuantity.desc: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

eligibleTransactionVolume.desc: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

maxPrice.desc: The highest price if the price is a range.

minPrice.desc: The lowest price if the price is a range.

price.desc:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.


      Usage guidelines:


Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of
      including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value.


      Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.


      Note that both RDFa and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values
      alongside more human-friendly formatting.


      Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

priceCurrency.desc: The currency (in 3-letter ISO 4217 format) of the price or a price component, when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

validFrom.desc: The date when the item becomes valid.

validThrough.desc: The end of the validity of offer, price specification, or opening hours data.

valueAddedTaxIncluded.desc: Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.

http://schema.org/Product.desc: Any offered product or service. For example: a pair of shoes; a concert ticket; the rental of a car; a haircut; or an episode of a TV show streamed online.

additionalProperty.desc:
A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org. 

Note: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

aggregateRating.desc: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

audience.desc: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

award.desc: An award won by or for this item.

awards.desc: Awards won by or for this item.

brand.desc: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

category.desc: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

gtin12.desc: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin13.desc: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13. Former 12-digit UPC codes can be converted into a GTIN-13 code by simply adding a preceeding zero. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin14.desc: The GTIN-14 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

gtin8.desc: The GTIN-8 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This code is also known as EAN/UCC-8 or 8-digit EAN. See GS1 GTIN Summary for more details.

isAccessoryOrSparePartFor.desc: A pointer to another product (or multiple products) for which this product is an accessory or spare part.

isConsumableFor.desc: A pointer to another product (or multiple products) for which this product is a consumable.

isRelatedTo.desc: A pointer to another, somehow related product (or multiple products).

isSimilarTo.desc: A pointer to another, functionally similar product (or multiple products).

itemCondition.desc: A predefined value from OfferItemCondition or a textual description of the condition of the product or service, or the products or services included in the offer.

model.desc: The model of the product. Use with the URL of a ProductModel or a textual representation of the model identifier. The URL of the ProductModel can be from an external source. It is recommended to additionally provide strong product identifiers via the gtin8/gtin13/gtin14 and mpn properties.

mpn.desc: The Manufacturer Part Number (MPN) of the product, or the product to which the offer refers.

offers.desc: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, or give away tickets to an event.

productID.desc: The product identifier, such as ISBN. For example: <meta itemprop='productID' content='isbn:123-456-789'/>.

productionDate.desc: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

purchaseDate.desc: The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.

releaseDate.desc: The release date of a product or product model. This can be used to distinguish the exact variant of a product.

sku.desc: The Stock Keeping Unit (SKU), i.e. a merchant-specific identifier for a product or service, or the product to which the offer refers.

weight.desc: The weight of the product or person.

http://schema.org/ProductModel.desc: A datasheet or vendor specification of a product (in the sense of a prototypical description).

isVariantOf.desc: A pointer to a base product from which this product is a variant. It is safe to infer that the variant inherits all product features from the base model, unless defined locally. This is not transitive.

predecessorOf.desc: A pointer from a previous, often discontinued variant of the product to its newer variant.

successorOf.desc: A pointer from a newer variant of a product  to its previous, often discontinued predecessor.

http://schema.org/ProgramMembership.desc: Used to describe membership in a loyalty programs (e.g. "StarAliance"), traveler clubs (e.g. "AAA"), purchase clubs ("Safeway Club"), etc.

hostingOrganization.desc: The organization (airline, travelers' club, etc.) the membership is made with.

member.desc: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

membershipNumber.desc: A unique identifier for the membership.

http://schema.org/Property.desc: A property, used to indicate attributes and relationships of some Thing; equivalent to rdf:Property.

domainIncludes.desc: Relates a property to a class that is (one of) the type(s) the property is expected to be used on.

inverseOf.desc: Relates a property to a property that is its inverse. Inverse properties relate the same pairs of items to each other, but in reversed direction. For example, the 'alumni' and 'alumniOf' properties are inverseOf each other. Some properties don't have explicit inverses; in these situations RDFa and JSON-LD syntax for reverse properties can be used.

rangeIncludes.desc: Relates a property to a class that constitutes (one of) the expected type(s) for values of the property.

supersededBy.desc: Relates a term (i.e. a property, class or enumeration) to one that supersedes it.

http://schema.org/PropertyValue.desc:
A property-value pair, e.g. representing a feature of a product or place. Use the 'name' property for the name of the property. If there is an additional human-readable version of the value, put that into the 'description' property.
        
        Always use specific schema.org properties when a) they exist and b) you can populate them. Using PropertyValue as a substitute will typically not trigger the same effect as using the original, specific property.

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

propertyID.desc:
A commonly used identifier for the characteristic represented by the property, e.g. a manufacturer or a standard code for a property. propertyID can be
(1) a prefixed string, mainly meant to be used with standards for product properties; (2) a site-specific, non-prefixed string (e.g. the primary key of the property or the vendor-specific id of the property), or (3)
a URL indicating the type of the property, either pointing to an external vocabulary, or a Web resource that describes the property (e.g. a glossary entry).
Standards bodies should promote a standard prefix for the identifiers of properties from their standards.

unitCode.desc: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

unitText.desc:
A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for
unitCode.

value.desc: The value of the quantitative value or property value node. For QuantitativeValue, the recommended type for values is 'Number'. For PropertyValue, it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.

valueReference.desc: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

defaultValue.desc: The default value of the input.  For properties that expect a literal, the default is a literal value, for properties that expect an object, it's an ID reference to one of the current values.

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

multipleValues.desc: Whether multiple values are allowed for the property.  Default is false.

readonlyValue.desc: Whether or not a property is mutable.  Default is false. Specifying this for a property that also has a value makes it act similar to a "hidden" input in an HTML form.

stepValue.desc: The stepValue attribute indicates the granularity that is expected (and required) of the value in a PropertyValueSpecification.

valueMaxLength.desc: Specifies the allowed range for number of characters in a literal value.

valueMinLength.desc: Specifies the minimum allowed range for number of characters in a literal value.

valueName.desc: Indicates the name of the PropertyValueSpecification to be used in URL templates and form encoding in a manner analogous to HTML's input@name.

valuePattern.desc: Specifies a regular expression for testing literal values according to the HTML spec.

valueRequired.desc: Whether the property must be filled in to complete the action.  Default is false.

http://schema.org/PsychologicalTreatment.desc: A process of care relying upon counseling, dialogue, communication, verbalization aimed at improving a mental health condition.

http://schema.org/PublicationEvent.desc: A PublicationEvent corresponds indifferently to the event of publication for a CreativeWork of any type e.g. a broadcast event, an on-demand event, a book/journal publication via a variety of delivery media.

free.desc: A flag to signal that the publication is accessible for free.

isAcccessibleForFree.desc: A flag to signal that the publication is accessible for free.

publishedOn.desc: A broadcast service associated with the publication event.

http://schema.org/PublicationIssue.desc:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or publication volume, often numbered, usually containing a grouping of works such as articles.

      See also blog post.

issueNumber.desc: Identifies the issue of publication; for example, "iii" or "2".

pageEnd.desc: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

pageStart.desc: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

pagination.desc: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

http://schema.org/PublicationVolume.desc:
A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or multi-volume work, often numbered. It may represent a time span, such as a year.

      See also blog post.

pageEnd.desc: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

pageStart.desc: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

pagination.desc: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

volumeNumber.desc: Identifies the volume of publication or multi-part work; for example, "iii" or "2".

http://schema.org/QAPage.desc: A QAPage is a WebPage focussed on a specific Question and its Answer(s), e.g. in a question answering site or documenting Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs).

http://schema.org/QualitativeValue.desc: A predefined value for a product characteristic, e.g. the power cord plug type "US" or the garment sizes "S", "M", "L", and "XL".

additionalProperty.desc:
A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org. 

Note: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

equal.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is equal to the object.

greater.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than the object.

greaterOrEqual.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than or equal to the object.

lesser.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than the object.

lesserOrEqual.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than or equal to the object.

nonEqual.desc: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is not equal to the object.

valueReference.desc: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

http://schema.org/QuantitativeValue.desc: A point value or interval for product characteristics and other purposes.

additionalProperty.desc:
A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org. 

Note: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

maxValue.desc: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

minValue.desc: The lower value of some characteristic or property.
