unitCode.desc: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

unitText.desc:
A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for
unitCode.

value.desc: The value of the quantitative value or property value node. For QuantitativeValue, the recommended type for values is 'Number'. For PropertyValue, it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.

valueReference.desc: A pointer to a secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature.

http://schema.org/Quantity.desc: Quantities such as distance, time, mass, weight, etc. Particular instances of say Mass are entities like '3 Kg' or '4 milligrams'.

http://schema.org/Question.desc: A specific question - e.g. from a user seeking answers online, or collected in a Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) document.

acceptedAnswer.desc: The answer that has been accepted as best, typically on a Question/Answer site. Sites vary in their selection mechanisms, e.g. drawing on community opinion and/or the view of the Question author.

answerCount.desc: The number of answers this question has received.

downvoteCount.desc: The number of downvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

suggestedAnswer.desc: An answer (possibly one of several, possibly incorrect) to a Question, e.g. on a Question/Answer site.

upvoteCount.desc: The number of upvotes this question, answer or comment has received from the community.

http://schema.org/QuoteAction.desc: An agent quotes/estimates/appraises an object/product/service with a price at a location/store.

http://schema.org/RVPark.desc: A place offering space for "Recreational Vehicles", Caravans, mobile homes and the like.

http://schema.org/RadiationTherapy.desc: A process of care using radiation aimed at improving a health condition.

http://schema.org/RadioChannel.desc: A unique instance of a radio BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

http://schema.org/RadioClip.desc: A short radio program or a segment/part of a radio program.

http://schema.org/RadioEpisode.desc: A radio episode which can be part of a series or season.

http://schema.org/RadioSeason.desc: Season dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

http://schema.org/RadioSeries.desc: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to radio broadcast and associated online delivery.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

containsSeason.desc: A season that is part of the media series.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

numberOfSeasons.desc: The number of seasons in this series.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

season.desc: A season in a media series.

seasons.desc: A season in a media series.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/Rating.desc: A rating is an evaluation on a numeric scale, such as 1 to 5 stars.

bestRating.desc: The highest value allowed in this rating system. If bestRating is omitted, 5 is assumed.

worstRating.desc: The lowest value allowed in this rating system. If worstRating is omitted, 1 is assumed.

http://schema.org/ReactAction.desc: The act of responding instinctively and emotionally to an object, expressing a sentiment.

http://schema.org/ReadAction.desc: The act of consuming written content.

http://schema.org/ReceiveAction.desc: The act of physically/electronically taking delivery of an object thathas been transferred from an origin to a destination. Reciprocal of SendAction..

deliveryMethod.desc: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

sender.desc: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the sending end of the action.

cookTime.desc: The time it takes to actually cook the dish, in ISO 8601 duration format.

cookingMethod.desc: The method of cooking, such as Frying, Steaming, ...

ingredients.desc: A single ingredient used in the recipe, e.g. sugar, flour or garlic.

prepTime.desc: The length of time it takes to prepare the recipe, in ISO 8601 duration format.

recipeCategory.desc: The category of the recipe—for example, appetizer, entree, etc.

recipeCuisine.desc: The cuisine of the recipe (for example, French or Ethiopian).

http://schema.org/SuperficialAnatomy.desc: Anatomical features that can be observed by sight (without dissection), including the form and proportions of the human body as well as surface landmarks that correspond to deeper subcutaneous structures. Superficial anatomy plays an important role in sports medicine, phlebotomy, and other medical specialties as underlying anatomical structures can be identified through surface palpation. For example, during back surgery, superficial anatomy can be used to palpate and count vertebrae to find the site of incision. Or in phlebotomy, superficial anatomy can be used to locate an underlying vein; for example, the median cubital vein can be located by palpating the borders of the cubital fossa (such as the epicondyles of the humerus) and then looking for the superficial signs of the vein, such as size, prominence, ability to refill after depression, and feel of surrounding tissue support. As another example, in a subluxation (dislocation) of the glenohumeral joint, the bony structure becomes pronounced with the deltoid muscle failing to cover the glenohumeral joint allowing the edges of the scapula to be superficially visible. Here, the superficial anatomy is the visible edges of the scapula, implying the underlying dislocation of the joint (the related anatomical structure).

mainEntityOfPage.desc:
Indicates a page (or other CreativeWork) for which this thing is the main entity being described.
      
      Many (but not all) pages have a fairly clear primary topic, some entity or thing that the page describes. For
      example a restaurant's home page might be primarily about that Restaurant, or an event listing page might
      represent a single event. The mainEntity and mainEntityOfPage properties allow you to explicitly express the relationship
      between the page and the primary entity.
      

      Related properties include sameAs, about, and url.
      

      The sameAs and url properties are both similar to mainEntityOfPage. The url property should be reserved to refer to more
      official or authoritative web pages, such as the item’s official website. The sameAs property also relates a thing
      to a page that indirectly identifies it. Whereas sameAs emphasises well known pages, the mainEntityOfPage property
      serves more to clarify which of several entities is the main one for that page.
      

      mainEntityOfPage can be used for any page, including those not recognized as authoritative for that entity. For example,
      for a product, sameAs might refer to a page on the manufacturer’s official site with specs for the product, while
      mainEntityOfPage might be used on pages within various retailers’ sites giving details for the same product.
      

      about is similar to mainEntity, with two key differences. First, about can refer to multiple entities/topics,
      while mainEntity should be used for only the primary one. Second, some pages have a primary entity that itself
      describes some other entity. For example, one web page may display a news article about a particular person.
      Another page may display a product review for a particular product. In these cases, mainEntity for the pages
      should refer to the news article or review, respectively, while about would more properly refer to the person or product.

The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.


      Usage guidelines:


Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of
      including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value.


      Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.


      Note that both RDFa and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values
      alongside more human-friendly formatting.


      Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use
          Action-based vocabulary, alongside types such as Comment.

http://schema.org/UserTweets.desc:
UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use
          Action-based vocabulary, alongside types such as Comment.

http://schema.org/Vehicle.desc: A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.

cargoVolume.desc:
The available volume for cargo or luggage. For automobiles, this is usually the trunk volume.
Typical unit code(s): LTR for liters, FTQ for cubic foot/feet

Note: You can use minValue and maxValue to indicate ranges.

dateVehicleFirstRegistered.desc: The date of the first registration of the vehicle with the respective public authorities.

driveWheelConfiguration.desc: The drive wheel configuration, i.e. which roadwheels will receive torque from the vehicle's engine via the drivetrain.

fuelConsumption.desc:
The amount of fuel consumed for traveling a particular distance or temporal duration with the given vehicle (e.g. liters per 100 km).
Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for liters per 100 km.
Use unitText to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. L/100 km.
Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, fuelConsumption (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and fuelEfficiency (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use valueReference to link the value for the fuel consumption to another value.

fuelEfficiency.desc:
The distance traveled per unit of fuel used; most commonly miles per gallon (mpg) or kilometers per liter (km/L).
Note 1: There are unfortunately no standard unit codes for miles per gallon or kilometers per liter.
Use unitText to indicate the unit of measurement, e.g. mpg or km/L.
Note 2: There are two ways of indicating the fuel consumption, fuelConsumption (e.g. 8 liters per 100 km) and fuelEfficiency (e.g. 30 miles per gallon). They are reciprocal.
Note 3: Often, the absolute value is useful only when related to driving speed ("at 80 km/h") or usage pattern ("city traffic"). You can use valueReference to link the value for the fuel economy to another value.

fuelType.desc: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

knownVehicleDamages.desc: A textual description of known damages, both repaired and unrepaired.

mileageFromOdometer.desc:
The total distance travelled by the particular vehicle since its initial production, as read from its odometer.
Typical unit code(s): KMT for kilometers, SMI for statute miles

numberOfAirbags.desc: The number or type of airbags in the vehicle.

numberOfAxles.desc:
The number of axles.
Typical unit code(s): C62

numberOfDoors.desc:
The number of doors.
Typical unit code(s): C62

numberOfForwardGears.desc:
The total number of forward gears available for the transmission system of the vehicle.
Typical unit code(s): C62

numberOfPreviousOwners.desc:
The number of owners of the vehicle, including the current one.
Typical unit code(s): C62

productionDate.desc: The date of production of the item, e.g. vehicle.

purchaseDate.desc: The date the item e.g. vehicle was purchased by the current owner.

steeringPosition.desc: The position of the steering wheel or similar device (mostly for cars).

vehicleConfiguration.desc: A short text indicating the configuration of the vehicle, e.g. '5dr hatchback ST 2.5 MT 225 hp' or 'limited edition'.

vehicleEngine.desc: Information about the engine or engines of the vehicle.

vehicleIdentificationNumber.desc: The Vehicle Identification Number (VIN) is a unique serial number used by the automotive industry to identify individual motor vehicles.

vehicleInteriorColor.desc: The color or color combination of the interior of the vehicle.

vehicleInteriorType.desc: The type or material of the interior of the vehicle (e.g. synthetic fabric, leather, wood, etc.). While most interior types are characterized by the material used, an interior type can also be based on vehicle usage or target audience.

vehicleModelDate.desc: The release date of a vehicle model (often used to differentiate versions of the same make and model).

vehicleSeatingCapacity.desc:
The number of passengers that can be seated in the vehicle, both in terms of the physical space available, and in terms of limitations set by law.
Typical unit code(s): C62 for persons

vehicleTransmission.desc: The type of component used for transmitting the power from a rotating power source to the wheels or other relevant component(s) ("gearbox" for cars).

http://schema.org/Vein.desc: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood to the heart.

drainsTo.desc: The vasculature that the vein drains into.

regionDrained.desc: The anatomical or organ system drained by this vessel; generally refers to a specific part of an organ.

tributary.desc: The anatomical or organ system that the vein flows into; a larger structure that the vein connects to.

http://schema.org/Vessel.desc: A component of the human body circulatory system comprised of an intricate network of hollow tubes that transport blood throughout the entire body.

http://schema.org/VideoGame.desc: A video game is an electronic game that involves human interaction with a user interface to generate visual feedback on a video device.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

gamePlatform.desc: The electronic systems used to play video games.

gameServer.desc: The server on which  it is possible to play the game.

playMode.desc: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

http://schema.org/VideoGameClip.desc: A short segment/part of a video game.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

characterAttribute.desc: A piece of data that represents a particular aspect of a fictional character (skill, power, character points, advantage, disadvantage).

containsSeason.desc: A season that is part of the media series.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

episode.desc: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

episodes.desc: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

gameItem.desc: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

gameLocation.desc: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

gamePlatform.desc: The electronic systems used to play video games.

numberOfEpisodes.desc: The number of episodes in this season or series.

numberOfPlayers.desc: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

numberOfSeasons.desc: The number of seasons in this series.

playMode.desc: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

productionCompany.desc: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

quest.desc: The task that a player-controlled character, or group of characters may complete in order to gain a reward.

season.desc: A season in a media series.

seasons.desc: A season in a media series.

trailer.desc: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

actor.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

actors.desc: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

director.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

directors.desc: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

thumbnail.desc: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

transcript.desc: If this MediaObject is an AudioObject or VideoObject, the transcript of that object.

videoFrameSize.desc: The frame size of the video.

http://schema.org/ViewAction.desc: The act of consuming static visual content.

http://schema.org/VisualArtwork.desc: A work of art that is primarily visual in character.

artEdition.desc: The number of copies when multiple copies of a piece of artwork are produced - e.g. for a limited edition of 20 prints, 'artEdition' refers to the total number of copies (in this example "20").

artMedium.desc: The material used. (e.g. Oil, Watercolour, Acrylic, Linoprint, Marble, Cyanotype, Digital, Lithograph, DryPoint, Intaglio, Pastel, Woodcut, Pencil, Mixed Media, etc.)

artform.desc: e.g. Painting, Drawing, Sculpture, Print, Photograph, Assemblage, Collage, etc.

artworkSurface.desc: The supporting materials for the artwork, e.g. Canvas, Paper, Wood, Board, etc.

material.desc: e.g. Oil, Watercolour, Acrylic, Linoprint, Marble, Cyanotype, Digital, Lithograph, DryPoint, Intaglio, Pastel, Woodcut, Pencil, Mixed Media, etc.

surface.desc: e.g. Canvas, Paper, Wood, Board, etc.

http://schema.org/VoteAction.desc: The act of expressing a preference from a fixed/finite/structured set of choices/options.

candidate.desc: A sub property of object. The candidate subject of this action.

http://schema.org/WPAdBlock.desc: An advertising section of the page.

http://schema.org/WPFooter.desc: The footer section of the page.

http://schema.org/WPHeader.desc: The header section of the page.

http://schema.org/WPSideBar.desc: A sidebar section of the page.

http://schema.org/WantAction.desc: The act of expressing a desire about the object. An agent wants an object.

http://schema.org/WarrantyPromise.desc: A structured value representing the duration and scope of services that will be provided to a customer free of charge in case of a defect or malfunction of a product.

durationOfWarranty.desc: The duration of the warranty promise. Common unitCode values are ANN for year, MON for months, or DAY for days.

warrantyScope.desc: The scope of the warranty promise.

http://schema.org/WarrantyScope.desc:
A range of of services that will be provided to a customer free of charge in case of a defect or malfunction of a product.

    Commonly used values:

    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Labor-BringIn 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-BringIn 
    http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-PickUp

http://schema.org/WatchAction.desc: The act of consuming dynamic/moving visual content.

http://schema.org/WearAction.desc: The act of dressing oneself in clothing.

browserRequirements.desc: Specifies browser requirements in human-readable text. For example,"requires HTML5 support".

http://schema.org/WebPage.desc: A web page. Every web page is implicitly assumed to be declared to be of type WebPage, so the various properties about that webpage, such as breadcrumb may be used. We recommend explicit declaration if these properties are specified, but if they are found outside of an itemscope, they will be assumed to be about the page.

breadcrumb.desc: A set of links that can help a user understand and navigate a website hierarchy.

lastReviewed.desc: Date on which the content on this web page was last reviewed for accuracy and/or completeness.

mainContentOfPage.desc: Indicates if this web page element is the main subject of the page.

primaryImageOfPage.desc: Indicates the main image on the page.

relatedLink.desc: A link related to this web page, for example to other related web pages.

reviewedBy.desc: People or organizations that have reviewed the content on this web page for accuracy and/or completeness.

significantLink.desc: One of the more significant URLs on the page. Typically, these are the non-navigation links that are clicked on the most.

significantLinks.desc: The most significant URLs on the page. Typically, these are the non-navigation links that are clicked on the most.

specialty.desc: One of the domain specialities to which this web page's content applies.

http://schema.org/WebPageElement.desc: A web page element, like a table or an image.

http://schema.org/WebSite.desc: A WebSite is a set of related web pages and other items typically served from a single web domain and accessible via URLs.

http://schema.org/WinAction.desc: The act of achieving victory in a competitive activity.

loser.desc: A sub property of participant. The loser of the action.

http://schema.org/WriteAction.desc: The act of authoring written creative content.

inLanguage.desc: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the IETF BCP 47 standard.

language.desc: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.
